text: all i can see in this picture is a woman in pain who feels she is not believed. i was sexually abused by a family member for years as a child. i was physically sick before i would visit him, yet my parents continued to send me there. when i was 18 and a legal adult, i broke off contact with this person, which was one of the most painful things i have ever had to do. i never saw my father again. when i was 18 and a legal adult, i told my parents about the abuse and i was told i was making it up for attention. let me tell you- there are so many easier ways for a young girl to get attention and naming an abuser is not one of them. the comment that i made this up for attention was almost more painful than the actual abuse. we must validate women‚Äôs reality when it comes to sexual assault. when i was in treatment for trauma, the therapists said that families who believed their family member got better faster. i stand with dr. ford and i believe you. #metoo #istandwithdrford #traumasurvivor #supportsurvivors #supportsurvivorsofsexualabuse #traumasurvivor

text:
when i was 14 i was touched by a senior from my high school who did not have my permission to do so. when i was 25, the same thing happened to me but this time it was a member of my close extended family who went too far. i immediately told my parents and had loved ones who believed me but on both occasions was called a drama queen by many who preferred to turn a blind eye. on top of that, i have been singled out and sexually harassed from the moment i hit puberty early on. these moments stay with you forever and you just can‚Äôt shake them off. i am a strong woman but no one is invincible. what is happening in our country right now is an absolute disgrace. i was dumbfounded that there were people who didn‚Äôt believe me...and my accusations didn‚Äôt regard someone who could sit on our supreme court. trust me, if you don‚Äôt know a woman who has been sexually harassed, assaulted, or raped, it means she doesn‚Äôt trust you enough to tell you. 
i am so sad and disgusted to see dr. ford go through this. republicans and democrats have a political agenda in this whole thing. i normally don‚Äôt let myself get involved emotionally in politics but i have had enough and it is affecting my core. dr. ford is such a brave woman and kavanaugh makes me want to throw up just by how he is holding himself during this whole process. i am not arguing whether or not of who is lying and who is telling the truth. i am merely venting over our government‚Äôs disgrace of how they are handling such a delicate situation. our government is letting me down but the only thing i can find solace in is that this country has had an awakening and people are beginning to rise up. 
women are not inferior to men. power does not excuse bad behavior. it‚Äôs as a simple as that...if you are smart enough to have power you should be smart enough to know this as common sense. 
#ibelieveher #stopkavanaugh #riseup #timesup #metoo #feministagenda #drford #womenempowerment #vote

text_retweet:
photo by @black.rabbit.poetry
.
""are any of you stupid men
and you preposterous women -
don‚Äôt think that i don‚Äôt see you,
disbelieving your sister
when she is in trouble
and disparaging her for 
a party that doesn‚Äôt want you -
are you really convinced
that the slings and arrows
of outrageous fortune
that come with stepping forward
as a survivor of sexual abuse
are taken lightly, without conviction,
or even remotely worth it 
if truth does not lie at the heart of it?
or is truth such a foreign concept
that you can‚Äôt imagine a single move
that isn‚Äôt politically charged
and dishonest?"
.
i am disgusted and furious that this is my country.
.
#dearprofessorford,
.
i got my first non-seasonal, part-time job at a super market in late summer the year i turned 17. there was a man there, who worked in the deli, who would often make inappropriate sexual comments to me, and at one point went so far as to grab my ass during work (in spite of my being a minor and he being older than my father). i was constantly afraid that he would find me alone in the back and try something else. thankfully nothing ever went further than that, but it definitely made going to work scary. i didn't think anyone would believe me, though, and that's #whyididntreport.
.
this is nothing compared with what you faced, but i think it's important that people know - sexual assault, harassment, etc. are far more widespread than people like to believe. just so you know, #metoo.
.

text: that one time we hung out poolside üëΩ‚ú® forever grateful for this human ‚ô•Ô∏è always seeing me as i am and loving me where i stand, even if it's at a distance because it's just what i needed in that moment. üòå boundaries are super important and being a sexual abuse survivor can make them hard to enact. i've grown a lot through my self healing, although it still happens everyday, the boundaries i've discovered can still be hard to display. im super grateful that i have (and have had) a partner that understands them and celebrates them.üåº surviving sexual abuse can make intimacy hard to do, especially the acts that naturally associate themselves when you grow closer to someone. trust is super important. feeling comfortable is super important. knowing what comfort feels like for you is super important. when i first started hanging out with kennybaby, i had already been non sexually active for around 2 years, even though i had an intimate partner in my life, sex was just something i struggled with enjoying - so i stopped.  as i embraced being solo, learning how to feel comfortable alone, handle everyday self care tasks - i decided i wanted to discover myself again through the lens of intimacy with others. my mantra was to love unconditionally with detachment. that's when i realized how special this human was to me. i never felt uncomfortable with him. i could speak my truths, lay my boundaries, and they were always respected. if my ptsd gets triggered, i still get scared and i still get nervous to share. but i fight to share and i find that acceptance is always there. i know that #metoo has created a platform, and i want to share that the weight that comes with surviving sexual abuse won't always feel so heavy and in my experience, debilitating. since accepting that i had survived rape and sexual abuse in 2010, i've put in lots of work to heal and that weight has lightened. i don't wake up everyday thinking about it, or when the thought does come up,  it doesn't ruin my day.  a lot of you know my personal struggle and story. i realize i'm not sharing the cases i've survived here, and if you know my story, thank you for holding space while i learned how to share it. ‚ô•Ô∏è

text:
this photo was taken about a week after i was sexually assaulted. one of the first things i did was chop off all my hair. i thought maybe changing the way i looked would change the way i felt. trying to cope with the reality of what had happened to me seemed impossible, and i struggled for months following the assault. today i‚Äôm sharing my story in hopes that my coming forward will encourage others to tell their story and know they‚Äôre not alone. for my senior project i want to explore the issue of sexual abuse in the united states. i don‚Äôt want this project to be just about statistics. i want real people with real stories. if you are a survivor of sexual abuse and feel compelled to share your story please take the time to fill out my survey. only i will see your responses, and they will be anonymous unless you state otherwise. the link is in my bio if you would like to participate. 
#metoo #himtoo #metoomovement #rapevictim #rapesurvivor #survivors #yourenotalone #istandwithyou #survivorsofsexualabuse #ibelieveher #ibelievehim

text:
"oh, they have done it now. they have done what thousands of feminists, hundreds of feminist organizations, and millions of women working as social and political activists over the years have not been able to do: they  have harnessed the power of a thousand hurricanes. it is not just that they have triggered the memories of every woman who has ever been sexually harassed or abused. now they have triggered the memories of every woman who has ever had her opinions ignored or her feelings scorned. ted cruz pointed out in his testimony that dr. ford was treated with respect. i suppose he means that because they didn‚Äôt throw eggs at her. what those men don‚Äôt understand is that being silent after hearing her speak, as though actually she had not spoken, does not show respect. basically ignoring what she said does not show respect. making it all about ‚Äúbrett, poor baby, he is one of us and he is hurting‚Äù does not show respect. in fact, their entire strategy now rests on ignoring what she said... not even grappling with her credibility, much less allowing a further  investigation or more witnesses to testify. and every woman who has ever felt that her words meant nothing, that they somehow disappeared into the air after she spoke them  and simply bounced off the ears of a man or men in the room, whether she was ever touched inappropriately or not, she is triggered now. congratulations, senators grassley, hatch, graham, cruz et al. you‚Äôve done it now. i think you might have just elected the first woman president. a fierce, giant force has just been awakened among us. and unlike quan yin sitting silently next to my television, we will not be silent. in the coming days and weeks and years, we will speak our truth. we will hear each other and we will believe each other. and this time, by men by by women alike, we will be heard. #justyouwait" - marianne williamson
@mariannewilliamson .

text: my story is important. my voice is important. i am important. equally as important. i am a survivor and we refuse to not be heard. not being believed by the people that can make the biggest difference can do some fucked up things to a victim‚Äôs head. i wasn‚Äôt believed. my mom wasn‚Äôt believed. i refuse to have my unborn children live in a world where if something were to happen to them, their biggest concern as a victim would be whether they can convince people that their story is truth or not. trauma doesn‚Äôt work that way. where it happens one day and then it‚Äôs over. my assault was 16 years ago and today. and though i choose to take my power back every single day, it‚Äôs still a conscious choice that requires effort and courage. #ibelieveher no matter when she chooses to speak. #36yearsagoandtoday #metoo

text:
‚Äúi will always believe you.‚Äù
.
realizing we have a middle schooler on our hands is wonderful and scary all at once... it‚Äôs a big world and you only get one chance to raise them.
while watching the news yesterday- we had a very raw, honest and age appropriate conversation about boundaries, saying no, belief, honesty, trust, and most importantly the fact that your body is yours alone and no one at any time or place has the right, the reason and the obligation to touch it. 
no matter what. .
we also talked about all the forms of saying no- including saying nothing at all... **there is no requirement to say no! nothing is enough.**
.
we also talked about how silence doesn‚Äôt equally lying.
and how the actions of others does not reflect upon you or define you.
.
we talked about how no matter what she said, when she said it, or whoever she said it about... i would believe her. period.
our children need to know this, they need to hear this.
.
.
so today, go find a child - boy or girl- and talk to them about all the uncomfortable, important things that need to be talked about... we must teach and show our children how to behavior and treat one another.
.
whatever the outcome, whatever political view you have... we are all humans, we all deserve respect, we all matter... so let‚Äôs make sure our children know it.
.
.
#ibelieveher #protect #helpthisgeneration #everythingwillcometolight #allofus #shematters #youmatter #illbeyourvoice #no #metoo #jesussendhelp #survivors

text:
friends, if you are feeling overwhelmed by life right now, or triggered by the recent senate hearing, please consider calling one of these numbers to vent or to find more resources or to just experience what it feels like to hear someone say ‚Äúi believe you, and i care‚Äù with no ‚Äúbut...‚Äù or ‚Äúat least...‚Äù following it.
~
it‚Äôs so easy to ignore abuse and discrimination when you‚Äôre not the one directly experiencing it, and it‚Äôs exhausting trying to get the unaffected to feel and see. ~
i encourage you to look up numbers in your local area, but you can call any hotline regardless of where you live. after talking to many people who have called in, i know it can feel weird to just dial a number and share your pain, but afterwards the majority of people only express relief and gratitude that someone was there to listen. we‚Äôre stronger together üíô
~
24-hour colorado sexual assault hotline, the blue bench (english): (303) 322-7273 
spanish: (303) 329-0031
https://thebluebench.org/

rainn national hotline: (800) 656-4673
https://www.rainn.org/

friends, if you are feeling overwhelmed by life right now, or triggered by the recent senate hearing, please consider calling one of these numbers to vent or to find more resources or to just experience what it feels like to hear someone say ‚Äúi believe you, and i care‚Äù with no ‚Äúbut...‚Äù or ‚Äúat least...‚Äù following it.
~
it‚Äôs so easy to ignore abuse and discrimination when you‚Äôre not the one directly experiencing it, and it‚Äôs exhausting trying to get the unaffected to feel and see. ~
i encourage you to look up numbers in your local area, but you can call any hotline regardless of where you live. after talking to many people who have called in, i know it can feel weird to just dial a number and share your pain, but afterwards the majority of people only express relief and gratitude that someone was there to listen. we‚Äôre stronger together üíô
~

..
for too long woman have gone unheard and mocked for coming forward. if dr ford had acted like kavanaugh had today. shouting, crying and interrupting while being questioned everyone would have labeled her unhinged and guilty. what because he is a white man in a high profile role it's deemed ok. bullshit.
..
trump also has the audacity to tweet "judge kavanaugh showed america exactly why i nominated him" why because he is a lying narcissistic arsehole. america needs to wake up. they swore into office a man that bragged about his treatment of woman on tape and had 19 credible accusations of sexual assaults against him but we can't speak about that because he is a man. fuck you trump and fuck you kavanaugh.
..
i am in awe of your bravery dr ford. as for you mr kavanaugh save your indignation because at last a woman is finally being heard.
.

when you unload the burden that others imposed on you, it shows and you can feel it in your soul. it is like an awakening of your senses and you realize just how much darkness enveloped you and your spirit.

.
apart from that, it was a good show. kept the audience engaged for the entire 1.25 hours, full of political sattire. if you aren't into politics, you won't probably enjoy this as much as political buffs would. but what good is humor if it is ridiculing a moment meant for uplifting survivors.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

there is emotional, sexual, verbal, reproductive, and digital abuse that people endure silently. well, it's not a secret anymore and i'm calling it out.

what are you gonna do?!?? feel free to let me know in the comments below.

text:
i don‚Äôt find it even a little believable that 100% these gop senators voting for kavanaugh are sure he didn‚Äôt do any of what he‚Äôs accused of doing. so let‚Äôs get that out of the way. most, if not all, doubt his innocence. flake said as much, which brings me to this point.

they aren‚Äôt saying they are sure he didn‚Äôt do it. they are saying they don‚Äôt care if he did. they are saying it was a long time ago and he shouldn‚Äôt have to pay forever. we should move on.

here‚Äôs the problem: she can‚Äôt move on. she will pay forever. not just dr. ford, but all the shes and hims and theys. all the people who were victimized in ways kavanaugh victimized women and girls will never be as they were before. sexual assault isn‚Äôt a crime that begins and ends, it‚Äôs a crime that lasts forever. it‚Äôs not shoplifting or cheating on a test or stealing a car. a storekeeper doesn‚Äôt have his or her life forever damaged because someone swiped a candy bar.

sexual assault is stripping someone of their privacy, agency, dignity, and bodily autonomy and leaving that experience with them forever. it means a lifetime of feeling like ripping your own skin off if a sight, sound, smell, or sensation triggers that memory. it means a lifetime of struggling to stay present when you‚Äôre trying to be intimate with someone you love. it means a lifetime of struggling with mental and sexual health. if it happened when you were young, say 15 or 11 or 4 or 7 or whatever, it means you will never know your sexual self that could‚Äôve existed if that never happened. it means a lifetime of telling partners why a certain phrase, touch, or sound ruins the mood for you. what sex offenders do to their victims is forever and it should be forever for the offender. what our lawmakers are saying is it‚Äôs okay for someone like me or you or dr. ford to pay forever but it‚Äôs not okay for someone like kavanaugh to pay at all.

we put people in prison forever for taking a life. in a way, sexual assault victims feel as though a part of our lives were taken. the least our country can do is keep our offenders out of the most prestigious judicial appointment in the country.

#electionsmatter #vote #kavanaugh #votethemout #gopgtfo #metoo

text: look at those hands. this is what it looks like to bear my soul. this is what it looks like to be vulnerable with a crowd, to tell the story that defines the last 2 years of my life, the tears and fears, and ultimate failing of the people and world around me. i may wish i hadn't had to go there, but i walked out of that dark place a stronger woman, with a deeper love and trust of the ones who helped me through. it feels fitting to show you this shot today. thanks to @mwirthphotography for the perfect capturing of my piece (i'll be sharing more of them as time goes on) and @rainbowmilitia for the safe environment to tell this tale. ‚ù§Ô∏è #metoo #bebrave #danceastherapy

text:
fighting friday.
-
you know my whole life.
-
i was always told what to say. 
how to dress.
how to act.
to fit inside a box if you will.
-
you should do the 9-5.
have a house.
have a dog.
be married.
do not curse and speak proper.
for that is what‚Äôs expected of you.
-
but the fact of the matter is.
if i conformed to these ideas that others have and not stay true to my own.
for me i would die.
-
my spirt would burn out.
my soul would wash away.
and i would never really be happy.
-
a favorite artist of mine @killrobbailey @hustlestandard said.
-
lock me up and i'll show you a fool. 
that's the truth.
show me a leash and i'll break all the rules.
cuz permission is wishin' that bitches would listen.
though my mission is killing.
i kill everything, my mental is vicious.
so vicious.
i do what i want, never give a f$@k.
this verse is my hit list.
middle fingers in the f$&king air if you're with this.
can i get a fu$@king witness.
-
-
always fight for who you are.
never apologize.
walk the road you want to walk.
and hold your damn head held high.
i promise you will only go on to do absolute great things.
-
so fight your truth on this fighting friday.
-

text:
i "don't care" about politics. 
i care about helping people, loving people, making people feel welcome and validated. 
i care about being a shoulder to lean on when trauma comes up. i believe in believing people's stories. i believe in being a safe space when someone opens up.

i choose who is around me. i no longer spend my time where i don't want to. i say no. 
i have mentors and influencers and inspirations. 
i know who surrounds you is a reflection of your worth as a person. what you think of yourself, others think of you. you teach people how to treat you. 
america, your president and electoral speak wonders of how you feel of your people, and of your country. these are the types of people you look up to and choose as leaders.

#fucktrump #endkavanaugh #mybody #metoo #ibelievedrford #ibelievechristineblaseyford #iseeyou

text:
trigger warning ‚ö†Ô∏è .
.
.
‚Äúi believe dr. ford
.
.
.
and i want to take this moment to point out that a young upper middle class white woman was afraid to come forward. with all of her wealth, access, and privilege. she was terrified. she was terrified even today. now take a moment to think about the women who have next to no social capital or financial backing that are sexually assaulted. if dr. ford was still terrified today even with the grace granted to white women, what do you think the rest of us go through when considering reporting sexual assault?‚Äù - courtney welch .
.
.
thank you for your bravery anita hill ... i recognize you for trailblazing woman‚Äôs rights in this space despite not getting the respect or notoriety you deserve until 30 years later. you need to be the face of this movement in a way that i feel supporters of ‚Äúwomen‚Äôs rights‚Äù is really not ready for. it‚Äôs imperative to understand the layers and intersections of sexual abuse for women of color (and the makeup of the legal audience you have to testify to) who too often get no local, yet alone national recognition or support. not to mention justice. there are lines of comparison in these two cases but race and class make these so vastly different. if you understand intersectionality then you must understand this immediately ... it‚Äôs more than simply saying you‚Äôre a ‚Äúfeminist‚Äù. solidarity requires real honesty - context! ‚ú® shoutout to my oakland shero kamala harris! she is one of the few politicians that i feel is working hard for the people ... especially in the court room‚ú® dr. ford‚Äôs victimhood/ survivorship needs to spark further conversation for black women & woc victims!
.
.
.

text:
‚ñ™Ô∏èi am infuriated by my country‚Äôs politicians. not only because of their complete lack of empathy, but also for their blatant abuse of our system to enhance their own self interests...
‚ñ™Ô∏èlet me ask you, and i really want you to think about this. let it settle.
‚ñ™Ô∏èford is a well educated, clinical psychologist. of all people she knows how our world handles accusations attempted rape. she knows that most offenders go unpunished, and that most women never come forward. she knows that unless you are videotaped or caught by law enforcement it is so hard to prove a case.. ‚ñ™Ô∏èshe knows that she is going to be circulated in the media, hung out to dry like laundry. she knows that she is going to get death threats and be publicly shamed. she knows that she will be sat in front of a committee of middle aged, rich, white men who could never understand what it is like to be in her position...she knows that she has sat with this for years. that in the beginning it consumed her, shaped her behavior, her world view, maybe even the profession she went into. as she got older i‚Äôm sure she pushed it back, fear of looking weak or less than kept her silent. even now, being successful, she can push it away...
‚ñ™Ô∏èbut when the man who attempted to rape her gets put up to be one of the most powerful men in our government. a human who will have the power to rule on rape cases. rule on laws on abortion. rule on pardoning the most powerful man in our country. maybe that is when it gets real. it‚Äôs not just her anymore. it‚Äôs now every other women who is in that situation. imagine this, imagine he was successful in his attempted rape, imagine she got pregnant. imagine he rolls back roe vs. wade. how messed up is that. i bet you she thought exactly this. i bet she thought it‚Äôs not just me anymore and this needs to stop. imagine, even though she knows it may not work, having to try because even 25 plus years later, those memories sting. they sting enough to endure harassment and public embarrassment, all for the hope that maybe our country won‚Äôt vote into power her attempted rapist...
.
#ibelieveher #hero #ibelieveyou #enoughisenough #metoo #christineblaseyford #dotherightthing

the one that says you. didn‚Äôt. win.

once again i was reminded why i didn‚Äôt say anything. 
once again i was reminded that some women, both those i know and don‚Äôt know will always support men over women. 
and once again, i was reminded that it‚Äôs a man‚Äôs world and how dare we do anything other than exist in it?

but even as i cried, i still believed. 
we‚Äôll persevere. 
we will persevere.
these tattoos tell my story. my story of survival. and in that story, i always win.

text:
this morning, @helenofmemphis and i sat together at @llcommissary. we opened up about layered stories that have long been locked inside over chai, chocolate and her #365circlesproject (swipe to see more).
.
i bet you know the layers... layers of not being believed. the impact not being believed has on silencing your voice. and the impact recovering your voice, even when shaky and wordless, has on healing.
.
we need each other. healing happens in community, not in isolation. healing is what the #metoo movement is all about. seeing ourselves and our stories in one another. knowing #youarenotalone. the experience of feeling seen and believed.

text:
it has been hard to see this whole event take place really. i absolutely believe her - and to witness the backlash, the denouncing, the apologies to kavanaugh for having to ‚Äúendure‚Äù this process...it reinforces in my mind and heart why so many, including myself, do not feel comfortable at all to speak up about our sexual abuse histories. i have a small women‚Äôs group online and when the #metoo movement started, we shared our own stories. sadly, most of our stories began in elementary - from the ages of 6-11 and did not stop there but shaped how we interpreted our self view, objectification, love, and our relationships. it‚Äôs heartbreaking to see a committee - primarily composed of middle-aged, wealthy, white men - continue to make the big decisions here that will ultimately shape our politics. 
i‚Äôm looking forward to the future - where hopefully we have people of color, differing backgrounds, and almost equal ratio of male to female facing the kavanaughs that  ivy league schools spit out and see how different it pans out. #ibelieveher

text: yesterday, i held my breath watching dr ford‚Äôs testimony and fought back tears as memories of something that i pushed out many years ago came flooding back. of my own experience with a drunk, aggressive male who thought he had the right to my body. but i was one of the lucky ones...in the aftermath i was lifted, supported and most of all- i was believed  by my friends & family; this made all the difference in my ability to heal emotionally. so thank you dr ford for your bravery yesterday, and thank you to my friends and parents who 15 years ago allowed me to be brave in speaking out about what had happened. can‚Äôt  imagine having been able to get through that without your support. i love you. sharing today in case it helps any one woman out their feel a little less alone in this. ‚ù§Ô∏è @jessilynn4141 @bjphillips121 @jennijessi1 @karynsundin @jennad0526 @dnuss8 photo: @hot_cross_puns_ #believeher #metoo

text_retweet:
reposting this bc i'm now able to articulate my thoughts better.  and while i did this pose originally for a yoga challenge...i'm using it as my outlet.  yoga has had a huge hand in helping me find myself.  and after watching the hearing with dr. blasey ford yesterday...i will be silent no more. 
11 years ago i was on a date with a guy i worked with during my internship.  things seemed to be going well, but once we got back to my apartment things took a turn.  he was very aggressive...forced himself on me...pinned my arms down.  i told him to stop multiple times.  i fought to free my arms.  and for a brief moment i gave up...thought to myself, "this is it.  i'm going to be raped." but i gave one last no! and threw him off me.  he immediately left... visibly mad.  he never talked to me again that summer...only to talk behind my back to other male co-workers... telling them i was a tease. 
i was lucky.

hearing dr blasey ford recount her sexual assault brought up feelings i had repressed for years.  i didn't tell anyone what happened, but does that make it less valid?  if i found out the guy that did that to me was running for a high power position, you'd be damn sure i would tell. 
i hear you dr blasey ford.  i believe you.  #ibelievechristineblaseyford #metoo #yogatherapy

text:
so here's the truth: as a female in this country, you probably know someone who has been raped, if you haven't been yourself. you most likely also know someone who has been sexually assaulted, if you haven't been yourself. and you definitely know someone who has been sexually harrassed, if you haven't been yourself. add those up, and nearly all of us have been subject to sexual misbehavior. all of us.

as such, the behavior described by dr. blasey ford is not news to the women in this country. what is news is that this woman stood up, like a f*cking superhero, and called it out in the most difficult arena imaginable.

although it appears that women will once again be let down today, i'm damned proud to be female.
.
.
.
#ibelieveher #metoo #timesup #thefutureisfemale #alllivesmatter #ibelievechristineblaseyford #imwithher

text:
09.28.2018: another new day of possibility. roller coaster of emotions from yesterday's display of white, male privilege and unfairness. on one side, i am angry and triggered. thinking of all my sisters with our collective stories and memories of sexual assault and sexual violence. yet here are...again, being told to shut up and sit down. on the other side, i am not surprised. seriously this country's foundation comes from white, male colonizers indoctrinated with the notion of privilege, supposed superiority, and subjugation of anybody not a white male. centuries later, nothing has changed. those colonizers, with their spittle-spewing outrage, angrily speaking about being unfairly treated, are hypocrites and amoral. sadly just as outrageous are the women who side with these men and treat their own affected sisters like the enemy. psh, *eyeroll.* last night i went to ceremony, prayed, sung those healing songs, and did what i could do in my own way. i prayed for all my sisters, including the misguided ones. as an indigenous woman, i carry resilience, fierceness, and toughness within my dna. my existence is my resistance. as hard as the colonizers tried to extinguish my ancestors, they persevered, so here i am to carry their legacy. by doing ceremony, i carry the spirit of all those strong women in my life. by doing ceremony, i toughen myself spiritually, physically, and mentally. i walk this warriorway and pray, sing, sacrifice for all those that need a boost. sisters, i believe you. sisters, i honor you. sisters, i hear you. collectively we carry so much strength within our core. we are rising to defeat this patriarchal, antiquated, ludicrous system. ironically social media is joining us all together to defeat this monster. i stand with you, sword unsheathed, ready to slay. üí™üî•‚úäüí•üóªüåà‚ú®
.
.
.
.
#indigenousresistance #warriorway #readytoslay #ceremony #strength #humility #perseverance #tough #navajoapache #femalewarrior #ibelieveher #metoo #whitemaleprivilege #notokavanaugh #trumpisachump

text:
silent all these years

____________

i was once in the very same shoes as dr. ford. maybe worse... and so i've lived the he said/she said game.  i know what happened, no matter what anyone else says. ‚áü
somehow, at such a young age, i was able to come out of that not blaming myself and being okay.  i found the courage to triumph over it.  but that doesn't mean i forgot.  we don't forget. and until this recent movement i never talked about it openly.  ever. it's taken me 36 years to be okay with sharing this because it's important.  it's time. and enough is enough. ‚áü
this isn't a political thing.  it's a 'this really happens... all the time... and it needs to stop" thing. ‚áü
raising a young man, one of the main things i needed to share with him when he got to a certain age was no means no. as parents, it starts at home.  someone's son is attacking someone's daughter (and yes, sometimes visa versa). please, have that ongoing conversation with your children - your boys and your girls.  make sure your girls have the confidence to say something and be clearly heard. there is a pervasiveness to sexual assault in our culture and it needs to stop. we just need the courage. and it's time.

text:
this photo was taken right before i went out to a concert. i was alone and tipsy during the show when i felt a man grinding on me. next thing i know, he had stuck his hand down the back of my white jeans and was grabbing my bare ass. the concert was emptying out and i searched the room for some sort of bouncer or someone to help me. instead, all i saw was a couple who were egging this man on, probably thinking we were a couple out for a good time. i wasn‚Äôt thinking clearly and couldn‚Äôt get it together to slap him or call the cops. that doesn‚Äôt make me any less of a victim. the fact that men think grabbing whoever, whenever is a right is disgusting. i‚Äôm lucky that it was in a public enough place that it didn‚Äôt go further. üôÖüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
when i was in college, i had a stalker who would repeatedly intimidate me, call me names, and switch class schedules to be in mine. i turned him in to our school‚Äôs safety department and had to participate in an investigation against him as i was the 5th girl he had done this to. i was asked to testify against him at the school‚Äôs hearing to have him expelled. i couldn‚Äôt do it because i was too scared to be in the same room as him. no one would come forward and testify against someone if something didn‚Äôt happen. clearly, even when things do happen, women don‚Äôt come forward because we don‚Äôt get help and people don‚Äôt care. the fact that people don‚Äôt believe dr. ford is mind-blowing to me. sharing her story is beyond brave and now she‚Äôs put herself in a position to be judged (when she‚Äôs a victim!) and receive death threats. she‚Äôs trying to protect this country from making a huge mistake that will last for the rest of kavanaugh‚Äôs despicable life. if you don‚Äôt understand why women can‚Äôt immediately come forward sometimes, you‚Äôve never experienced an assault, whether it‚Äôs mental or physical. if you support kavanaugh, i pray to god that you don‚Äôt have daughters who grow up alongside men who have been taught by example that assault is acceptable. if you don‚Äôt believe dr. ford and you‚Äôre not in support of believing other victims, i‚Äôm sending you a special invite to unfollow me. thank you. üëãüèª

text:
if you want to know #whyididntreport go look at what‚Äôs happening in the media when women come forward. go look at the influencers have spoken out recently and read the comments under their pictures. go see how difficult it is for women to tell their stories and be taken seriously when they‚Äôve experienced horrific and life altering trauma.  believe me, i wish that any of the times i was sexually assaulted i had a nice little file folder of evidence dropped in front of me. but i don‚Äôt. i wasn‚Äôt thinking ‚Äúlet me ask this guy‚Äôs name and call out for witnesses‚Äù as i was lucky enough to be running away from a stranger who was trying to rape me. 
if you want to know #whyididntreport the last time i was sexually assaulted, you‚Äôll need to know what happened the times that i did. in high school when i reported hallway gropings and being followed on my walks home, i was labeled a bitch and bullied. the administration did nothing bc boys will be boys. another  time i did report was to my employer after an employee cornered me and began forcing himself on me during our shift. i was sent home for the day and he was never even questioned. i was told to drop it because i was causing friction. if you want to know #whyididntreport you‚Äôd have to know what it felt like to be drugged and followed into a parking lot, groped (etc), and forcibly dragged towards someone‚Äôs car against your will. you‚Äôd have to know what it felt like to know that if your bf didn‚Äôt believe you, the police probably wouldn‚Äôt bc i didn‚Äôt even know his name. you have to know what it felt like to be told but nothing actually happened to you since you weren‚Äôt actually raped. if you‚Äôd want to know why i didn‚Äôt report you have to live the sum of my life experiences in a society that has done nothing to make me feel safe. if you want to know, i will tell you bc i can, bc i have my voice and i want to use it, bc i won‚Äôt be quiet anymore, but make no mistake i don‚Äôt owe anyone any explanation. for those of you really truly feel compelled to ask why i and so many others didn‚Äôt report, i feel compelled to tell you that you are asking the wrong questions. #headhighheartforward

text: yesterday, a woman stood in front our our nation and shared her story of being sexually assaulted by a man.  she did not have the protection of the rape shield laws in this country, she did not have the privilege or the hope of justice.  she had no privacy to heal, no protection from the media and the hate filled commentary that follows.  she walked into a room filled with men, reporters, video cameras and shared her experiences with the world.  simply because she believed it was her civic duty to do the right thing.  she shared how it felt to think she was dying while her attacker covered her screams and she felt she could not breathe.  she shared her pain, her private experiences in therapy with her husband, the memories she struggles with still today.  yesterday - we saw the strength and the courage it takes to stand tall in your truth.  the passion to do the right thing - even in the space of constant judgement, criticism and hate.  as a woman who knows what it feels like to not be able to breathe, who knows what it feels like to think you will die if you can not find a way to escape your attacker- i want to thank her for standing tall, for her courage to tell our story and for her willingness to confront a lifetime of painful memories .  your voice rises up and represents all of us who have remained quiet for far too long.  i stand with you. i believe you and i support you.  thank you for your courage dr. christine blasey ford. stand tall.

#repost @laurenmarxart i share her sentiments, as a survivor of sexual assault myself. „Éª„Éª„Éª
i rarely post anything personal, or any social commentary, but with the kavanaugh hearing, and his nomination to the supreme court, i must say something. i believe christine blasey ford. i was also sexually assaulted. the fear and shame attached to an event is hard to describe and cope with. try to have an empathetic and understanding heart. .
sexual assault is more common that we as society are prepared to admit. whether you know it or not, someone very close to you has been assaulted. these are some of the broad reasons why: fear of no one believing you, fear of being "slut-shamed", fear of assault, fear of career assassination, and denial of the events keeps people from coming forward immediately. .
i believe you. we believe you.
.

text: it's not easy talking about it. i, too, was touched, molested and almost raped at different times growing up. i've only told a couple of people because i was embarrassed, shocked and was somehow able to block what a cousin did to me at the age of 5 or 6, i can't remember (it came back to me when i was 17 or 18 as i was driving up boston ave.. i'm not sure what triggered this repressed memory) . when time passes, you don't remember certain things. for example, i can't remember the exact ages when each instance happened, what year, what one of the people even looks like, etc. i do remember things like the walls (i don't remember the house though), the floor, the color of the wall, the pants they were wearing, the color sweater one was wearing, the weather, etc etc... #ibelieveher #delaythevote #metoo

text: i‚Äôve had a tough week. a week ago today, i woke up with some scary symptoms and spent the day having tests and lots of blood drawn (the tech even punctured the vein in one arm and had to start again on the other one - still bruised from the puncture). then, i had to wait over the weekend and into tuesday morning to learn all tests were ‚Äònegative,‚Äô meaning none of the scary things they were looking for were found, indicating it was most likely a virus with weird manifestations, which actually escalated during the waiting period, leaving me bedridden for four days... horrible timing (as if there ever is a ‚Äògood‚Äô time for that sort of thing), given the fact that we were babysitting two of our grandkids while their parents were in ca for a wedding. fortunately, the other adults in the house took over - completely. plus, my wonderful wise knower of all things to improve health (@sproutyou ) gave me lots of great support. i‚Äôm on the mend, just as we head out of state. the city where we are visiting is a tough place for me to be. there‚Äôs a river that runs through the heart of the town, and in the river is an island where my brother died 29 years ago. coming back is a big ol‚Äô mixed bag... compounded by the emotions stirred up from yesterday‚Äôs senate committee hearing with dr ford and that other man. i‚Äôm trying to be less frantic, and instead be more like the regal, wise, patient, watchful owl that visited outside my meditation space on wednesday. she was waiting in the tree out front during a time when things were frantic in my house, and the universe sent her to remind me to be more like her. i‚Äôve forgotten from time to time in the last 48-hours, but at least i can try, and try again...

text:
yesterday i watched the hearing with dr. christine blasey ford throughout the day as she testified before millions, reliving her trauma of sexual assault. it was extremely hard for me and i‚Äôm sure thousands of other sexual assaulted survivors to hear her story. it brought back all of my memories that i buried so deep, and they are just on replay, in detail over and over again.it‚Äôs been torture and it‚Äôs exhausting. .
#whyididntreport 
the girl in this picture was sexually abused when she was 6 years old. she didn‚Äôt report it because she was 6 years old. she didn‚Äôt understand what was happening. it went on for 7 years and she didn‚Äôt know it wasn‚Äôt normal. she didn‚Äôt report it because he was family and was respected and loved by everyone. she thought because she was adopted she wasn‚Äôt seen as a ‚Äúreal‚Äù member of the family and that that is why it was happening. she thought if she told she would be sent back to foster care. she didn‚Äôt report because when she was old enough to finally realize that everything that happened was extremely wrong she thought maybe she somehow deserved it. she tried to tell her parents years later but was told she was remembering it wrong, that it must‚Äôve happened when she was with a different foster family. but if she was remembering it right it was ok because he had a disease that excused him.  she is still too scared to say his name because she fears what her family will think about her or what they will say. .
i am terrified and physically shaking from the fear of posting this. but i am sharing  because i am tired of feeling ashamed for something i had no control over, for something that wasn‚Äôt my fault. i‚Äôm tired of agreeing with people who say they don‚Äôt believe survivors because i am scared of what they will say about me. i want to be brave and speak and fight about this so that shit  actually starts to change. i never wanted this. and neither did the thousands of other sexual assault survivors. it‚Äôs time to stop asking why women don‚Äôt report and start asking why we are being harassed , abused and raped every single day! why are we being ignored, shamed and blamed? it‚Äôs time to #belivesurvivors

text:
today republican senators seek to remind women to know their place. their actions say to us that the gop agenda is more important than the truth. more important than the soul of our nation or the power of our democracy. it may feel like we are powerless as we watch it take place, but i assure you we are not! regardless of the outcome of this vote, we determine if these senators still have their jobs next year. volunteer, protest, mobilize, donate and vote! that is how outrage turns into power.

#metoo #believewomen #supportwomen #vote #womenvote #stopkavanaugh

text:
a simultaneously celebratory and deeply healing gathering of highly tuned in women last night!
üå∏ 
we are fortunate to have this and you can have it too. i have more than one sacred circle of friends and it‚Äôs like art to see how they weave together, or gracefully exist side by side in the same atmosphere of higher consciousness. they include fine men too.
üå∏
if you follow this page and my *stories i will be showing you how.
i will share everything i know that has been and is unfolding for me; how to find and live your purpose, how to create the most loving relationships, how to find balance, how to shine, in devotional internal ways, in very practical logistical ways, for your missions, your business, your message to the world, via writing, social media, wherever you can reach *more people to share your gifts and messages, because we need elevated thinkers, creators and helpers more than ever.
we have such power together + add technology and open minds of all ages in all gender recipes~ quantum leap!
üå∏
it takes bravery, vulnerability and a high integrity to hold a safe space for others, but right now, today, the volume has been turned up (again) for women.
üå∏
forecasting the ultimate message we are collectively receiving right now about the divine feminine wound (imbalance with the divine masculine), earlier this week, i wrote a piece, a message that i had to type out at 3am, the evening of the full moon of course!
it will be the post to follow this one later today or tomorrow.
üå∏

text:
i am really moved from the tidal emotion of the current events. namely #christineblaseyford  #believesurvivors #ibelieveher. if you haven't looked it up i suggest you do. for me it's the second wave after #metoo and the #metoomovement that is meant to leave some permanent change regarding #womensrights and #sexualabuse and #sexualassault
..
i've only watched a couple of things this morning and i know with my whole being and soul that this is it. #timesup old systems and paradigms are dying for good. toxicity, abuse and suffering are up in the light to be dealt with, blasted and transmuted into love, equality and appreciation.
..
my guess is that next on the map of cosmic healing is #emotionalabuse. i personally haven't suffered from sexual abuse, assault or harassment (although i do have my doubts, perhaps i'm still in denial) but know for sure i've had a fair share of emotional neglect and abandonment, and that it's been carried over for generations in my family.
..
emotional abuse is invisible and hard to pinpoint. it took me 34 years to identify and name it - the reason for my suffering my whole life. nonetheless, it's most damaging. many argue that it's actually worse than any physical abuse (not meaning to diminish it).
..
emotional abuse is the denial, betrayal, rejection and the abandonment of your most real self, of everything that makes you - you. it starts from the day you're born and the damage is already done by the time you're three or four. you never get a chance to develop your own healthy ego and sense of self.
..
and that is done by your primary caregivers - the only people you know, the people you trust, love and would do anything for. even abandon yourself in order to receive their fleeting approval, appreciation and care. and care - your physical survival depends on them.
..
to me #emotionalabuse is the ultimate denial and rejection of the self and soul. it's a #soulmurder
..
something to think about.
.
.
üì∑ @onbeinginyourbody üôè

text: seriously is this chick gunna try to bring the kid down in 40 years when he becomes someone in the public eye who has success, a family he loves and notoriety? sometimes i'm embaressed to be a woman in this day and age. say what you want, but this is all getting ridiculous. just because someone cries sexual assault it is not automatic guilt, no matter if the so called guilty party is a man or woman. if you people listen to half of what was said today and read other accounts and knew the background you'd have a different view. a-i don't believe this happened in the way it is being claimed-if it even happened at all. and b-if it did in some form, hasn't everyone in their teens, twenties or even thirties done something or acted a way in which they regret. god knows i did. does it make me less of a person, or less likely to be able to do my job or anything else i may do for the rest of my life? absolutely not. and this goes for a good majority of people. we have to stop automatically thinking that someone who may have made a mistake at one point in their life no longer deserves the life they've made for themselves since that point. the way people are tossing accusations so publicly from 15, 20, 30, forty years ago and ruining successful peoples lives is absolutely sickening.  we're all so quick to take each other down with one accusation without all of the facts. it's not all right or all wrong, just like no person is all good or all bad. it's what makes us human. but we sensationalize people or an event for the point of getting more eyes on a story because of how fast news moves today, it seems the true story gets lost and people lose everything they've worked for. there has to be a better way to go about this. @people #metoomovement #kavanaugh #drford @mattlauer_ #lesmoonves  #millenials #metoo #democrats #republicans #women #politics @cbsnews @nbcnews #standwithkavanaugh #confirmkavanaugh

text:
professor anita hill spoke this morning at #ghc18, at a session titled: ‚Äúthe past, present, and future of the #metoo movements.‚Äù
at the end of q&a she had a question for us. i‚Äôve paraphrased because my typing skills suck, but i feel this is important for people to hear right now:
there will be a decision made in the senate today, and many of us are going to feel disappointed and betrayed. what are you going to do? how are you going to respond? a natural response is to throw up your hands. and maybe move to france. or canada. i had a choice to make 27 years ago. i wanted to do nothing more than retreat back to my world and say nasty things about the us senate. i did say nasty things about the us senate. but i did not retreat. you do not have a choice about what they do, but you do have a choice about what -you- do. what are you going to do to make the world a more positive place?

text:
i rarely post anything personal, or any social commentary, but with the kavanaugh hearing, and his nomination to the supreme court, i must say something. i believe christine blasey ford. i was also sexually assaulted. the fear and shame attached to an event is hard to describe and cope with. try to have an empathetic and understanding heart. .
sexual assault is more common that we as society are prepared to admit. whether you know it or not, someone very close to you has been assaulted. these are some of the broad reasons why: fear of no one believing you, fear of being "slut-shamed", fear of assault, fear of career assassination, and denial of the events keeps people from coming forward immediately. .
i believe you. we believe you.
.

text:
day 07 of #100daysofhealing .
.
i woke up with a heavy heart after watching the response of a large majority after dr. ford‚Äôs hearing. beyond what our stand on this particular case is, we need to treat survivors with empathy and respect. .
surviving sexual violence is a life long journey.
.
i‚Äôd like to share a poem i wrote a year ago on a somber day like today. may this bring you hope and carry you forward.
.
i choose to be the light i want to see.
i choose the light i know we all need.
i choose to be the light that shines, fueled by my dreams and hopes, my warmth and my love.
my light. this light that was born from my own darkness and fears, my pain and my tears.
my light. this light that pierces through me, because no darkness, no fear and no pain, will ever be strong enough, hard enough, large enough to extinguish it.
from this moment on: i choose to be the light. this infinite and imperfect light.
for as long as i live, my light will shine, for my sisters and brothers.
may this light ignite yours, for that is, my only true hope. by @marthalluch .
.

text: i was blindsided by my reaction, listening to the hearing yesterday. none of the #metoo stories have had this effect on me. i've read and listened, as a fellow survivor, w somewhat detached compassion and empathy. yesterday tho was different & i was unprepared.  dr fords recollection of the laughter set something off in me. kavenaughs subsequent sniveling, playing-victim-arrogance unleashed a rage i've rarely felt. listening to him had a very real physical effect on me, as i waivered between fight and flight. i still waiver... i want to take to the streets as much as i want to pull the covers over my head. so i guess i'll head to the studio and hammer the fuck out of some metal.  #ibelieveher #isupporther #ibelievechristineblaseyford #survivor #truth #vote #vote #vote #hammertime

text:
this isn‚Äôt a political post. 
i‚Äôm sure that anyone with a background in studying mental health and working within the sector (as i did for 20+ years) can attest - the most prominent thing about watching these confirmation hearings is that we know the trauma that it is currently causing. the fear that it is putting in people to ever come forward. the pain and ptsd symptoms that it is triggering. for anyone struggling, please just know that you‚Äôre not alone. please utilize your healthcare mental health resources. if you do not have access to resources, please don‚Äôt hesitate to send me a direct private message and i can help you find low income or free resources in your community. most of all, please just know that you‚Äôre not alone in this.  if you just need someone to talk to please use one of the numbers listed below:

national sexual assault hotline
operated by rainn, the nation‚Äôs largest anti-sexual violence hotline.
1-800-656-hope 
time's up
time's up addresses the systemic inequality and injustice in the workplace that keep underrepresented groups from reaching their full potential. they partner with leading advocates for equality and safety to improve laws, employment agreements and corporate policies; help change the face of corporate boardrooms and the c-suite; and enable more women and men to access our legal system to hold wrongdoers accountable.
#timesup 
the me too movement
founded by tarana burke over 10 years ago to encourage victims of sexual harassment and assault to speak out about their experiences.
#metoo 
nova: national organization for victim assistance
a private, nonprofit organization committed to recognizing victims' rights in four areas: national and local legislative advocacy, direct victim assistance, member support and professional development. 
9to5: national association of working women
dedicated to improving working conditions and ensuring the rights of women and families.

thank you dr. christine blasey ford

text:
there‚Äôs not much i like about myself today if we‚Äôre being completely honest. watching this whole kavanaugh thing this week has really brought up a lot of unwanted memories of my own traumas that i try so hard to forget. 
i am filled with anger that this innocent man is being accused of such horrible things and this despicable woman is taking away from true survivors of trauma like myself. 
stop calling her brave. she‚Äôs a fucking liar. 
you can choose to not seek out justice and still be brave and strong as hell. a lot of us cannot seek out the justice that we deserve because a lot of times it is our word against our attackers. 
the men who took what wasn‚Äôt theirs may not get justice on this earth but they will face consequences and judgement someday. 
that‚Äôs what i have to chosen to believe. 
i make my own justice by making myself physically and mentally stronger every day and not choosing to be a victim. i am not what happened to me. i am choosing forgiveness which is a victory in and of itself. and i am choosing to keep on living the life i‚Äôve been blessed with because letting what happened consume me and continue to destroy my life just gives these cruel men power over me. 
p.s.‚Äînot all men are trash‚Äîthere are good men out there that are just and kind and godly and will do wonderful things for their families and this country. let‚Äôs empower them again to do that and stop trying to take away their voices as we continue to push this #metoo shit. 
i have so much more to say on this. maybe i‚Äôll write another blog about it... if you‚Äôve read up to this point you rock üí™üèª
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢

text:
this day is not big enough to hold the enormity of my rage. it‚Äôs a quake in my arms, a thump in my chest, a clench in my jaw. every woman i know is #christineblaseyford. every woman i know is #anitahill. every woman has a story something like theirs, or worse. 
they are the true embodiment of courage and heroism - contrasted against the ugliest white male fragility, fear, and entitlement. 
in the kali stories of the hindu tradition, after kali slays a demon she is often so intoxicated with rage that she begins to burn the whole world down. today i understand how she feels, why she does it. because the rage is just so big & the structure which nurtured the demon so toxic. 
#christineblaseyford #believesurvivors #believewomen #metoo #timesup #ibelieveher #stopkavanaugh #getoutthevote #vote #smashthepatriarchy #feminist

text: here‚Äôs the issue: there are people who are taking a woman‚Äôs confession of a sexual assault and making it a part of a political agenda. this is not about politics. this isn‚Äôt about conservative or liberal, democrat or republican. this is so much bigger than that. and i don‚Äôt want to hear the excuses. any non consensual sexual act is assault. don‚Äôt care if either of them are drunk. don‚Äôt care if it‚Äôs penetrative sex, groping, grinding, or anything else. boys will not be boys. boys will face the consequences of their actions just like girls will. i don‚Äôt care if it was 35 years ago or 35 days. yes, it is more than possible for a victim to block out past trauma so that details are muddled or indistinguishable, and in fact it is a very common coping mechanism of the body. she has stated that she went forward to her representative about the assault before kavanaugh was ever nominated for the supreme court. what kind of message does picking apart a sexual assault survivor on national television for political purposes send to those who have been through similar trauma and haven‚Äôt come forward about it? i believe dr. christine blasey ford, and i stand with her. not out of political persuasion. not out of social standing. but for the sake of every other woman, man, and child who have been victim of a sexual assault: i believe you. #ibelieveher #metoo #timesup

text:
the most shocking news from the #metoo movement was learning that almost every girl i knew had a story to tell.  it was really sad knowing so many victims have not even been able to confide in their friends for support, and that is reasonable. if i didn‚Äôt have a therapist i probably would have tried to suppress some memories so far down that i would question if the event was a nightmare or reality.  dr. blasey ford‚Äôs testimony was nothing short of heroic. the ability to speak articulately and coherently while simultaneously reliving a traumatic experience is not a skill many people have.  no matter the outcome, i hope people gain an understanding of what sexual misconduct is.  i am optimistic that as survivors are standing up for themselves, and teaching the masses what is not acceptable, behaviors will change. .
.
#reclaimingmytime

text: i only follow politics enough to know the government is pretty fucked up & people are angry. it can be maddening to live in a world that seems to be regressing ü§¨ but i see a lot of progress, too. what‚Äôs amazing is how many women are standing up for what they believe, speaking out, & supporting one another üëäüèº i grew up in a small town & it felt like there was this underlying competition & separateness amongst the girls i went to school with. girls were so mean & they bullied each other. it was so sad because looking back, we were all going through the same weird, hormonal stuff & just trying to figure it out ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è when i moved away, i had a completely different experience. i enrolled in yoga teacher training & met 2 incredible ladies who are still 2 of my best friends today. we always lift each other up. the all girls college i graduated from was another amazing example of women empowering one another & empowering themselves. today, i have a tribe of warrior women i get to call friends. we are happy for each other‚Äôs happiness & have an abundance mindset when it comes to beauty & success. a vulnerability exists between us where we openly discuss our pain & challenges because we feel safe, not judged. it‚Äôs beautiful & powerful üî• i‚Äôm pretty removed from life as a middle school or high school girl. but i remember how hard it was, how much i hurt & how much i cried in those days. my hope is that young girls are paying enough attention to know we ladies need to stick together, have each other‚Äôs back & be kind. i hope they realize all women deal with objectification, harassment in one form or another & the glass ceiling. the only way out is through & we need to get through this together. women for women...always üíó #womenempowerment #womenforwomen #pussypower

text: as a multiple time sexual assault survivor from childhood through my adulthood, i struggle with ptsd and panic/anxiety disorder with agoraphobia. it affects every facet of my life. it affects every day of my life. i'm blessed with a gifted psychologist who has taught me coping skills which, coupled with medication allow me to function in the necessities of life. each time i attempted to tell someone what happened to me, i wasn't believed or was blamed in some way. after a while, you just accept it and try to simply survive. current events have increased my anxiety and nightmares. i find myself reliving events and withdrawing from the world. having the impact of these assaults diminished and dismissed is horrendous. it can even be life threatening as it can cause suicidal thoughts... and plans. if you struggle, as i do, you're not alone. and if you know someone who is a survivor, reach out to them. these are difficult times. #survivor #ptsd #anxiety #panicdisorder #agoraphobia #rapesurvivor #sexualassaultsurvivor #whyididntreport #disabledveteran #disabledusafveteran #usafveteran #mst #noisno #metoo #metoomovement

my fb after an elder in my family @ me regarding a comment i made under of my cousins post on bill cosby. this elder although as sweet as can be is clearly still living in the era of "boys will be boys" and a woman should "know better" . that shit is long gone and is exactly why although people get turned off by my raw truth i continue to tell it because when i was experiencing these situations i didn't know who i could trust and turn to, even worse who would believe me especially about their dad or granddad. i did tell on my friends grandfather it caused us to stop being friends and over 20 years later when we saw each other she told me how her grandfather actually raped her. i told on my stepfather but was labeled a troubled child and liar, i told on the lady father in indiana and had the longest silent ride back to fort drum from his daughter who hated me. then when we got back she told the pastor and church trying to say i was possessed and a liar. by the time i was supposed to be in safe places instead of telling i just started running away and really got a name for myself as a troubled teen. i was troubled but not in the way many thought. i mean shit i ran away one time text:
eight years ago my world shattered. eight years ago i experienced extreme trauma and would forever be changed. if you‚Äôve followed my story you know why the me too movement and everything happening in the news right now is literally apart of my heart. i stand and pray with dr. ford this week, i support the women finding bravery and courage everyday to own the trauma apart of their story to create strength, bravery, and love among this tribe of women around the world fighting for us. üëèüèΩüëèüèΩüëèüèΩ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
it‚Äôs been eight years of healing from virginity that was taken from me. it‚Äôs been eight years of healing from feeling completely broken. it‚Äôs been eight years of finding strength to see myself as beautiful after feeling empty inside. would i ask for this trauma? hell no. but i am a stronger person than i thought possible. i know what it means to question everything in life and within the darkness you decide you‚Äôre worthy of bringing light to the dark and to the world. it‚Äôs eight years of learning truly, what grace to myself means and allowing myself space to live in the hard places. it‚Äôs eight years of trusting myself again and my body after it froze eight years earlier and didn‚Äôt defend itself. it‚Äôs eight years of healing upon healing and here i am, still living. deciding to thrive and not just survive and know i‚Äôm worthy. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
if you‚Äôre a women that feels alone, that‚Äôs struggling with trauma or feelings of worthiness, reach out to loved ones. reach out to me. there is a tribe of women out there fighting for women to feel strong, heard and relevant in this world. will you join us? üåé‚ú®

text: i don‚Äôt like sharing things like this but i am at the point where i am fed up. i am angry, sad, lost for words and so many other emotions i can‚Äôt explain. after the painful hearing for kavanaugh yesterday i feel like i should share how i truly feel. i know i am not alone but i also know many people don‚Äôt have the ‚Äúcourage‚Äù to say anything. sexual abuse and assault is not a joke. it is something that impacts a victim for the rest of their live. sure, moments of that experience fade away but the pain is always there. it also doesn‚Äôt matter if it happened this year or 30 years ago. what matters is it happened and there‚Äôs still pain. this mentality of boys will be boys or they were young and drinking doesn‚Äôt mean it isn‚Äôt assault or it never happened. i strongly disagree with senator graham when he had the balls to support a man who sexually assaulted a women. point blank. to say that kavanaugh‚Äôs life for the last few weeks have been hell is a joke. once again we are taking sides of someone who committed a crime and more or less laughing at the victim. i am sick and tired of this. this shouldn‚Äôt be a political debate. it shouldn‚Äôt even be a debate at all. it‚Äôs so easy to stand with everyone but if you disagree be courageous and be the one person standing alone. all it takes is one person. #courage #sexualassualt #kavanaugh #stopkavanaugh #metoo #2018 #standalone

text:
the fear of abandoment is real.
the anxiety that is buried deep feels constant.
& lingering emptiness seems unjust.
¬∑
as we travel deeper and as we explore the galaxies of our inner worlds, sometimes we stumble upon wounds still dormant and healing left undone.
¬∑
the hurt that was once experienced left an imprint in our minds and a hole in our hearts that we alone were left to heal, whether we were ready to or not.
¬∑
but regardless of how we were hurt or what was stolen, sometimes the pain is too much to bare or our minds too young to fully understand. and the need to simply survive takes over because as we know, the world doesn't stop just because the one within you comes crumbleing down
¬∑
so we left the truth hidden, both from ourselves and the world. placed it in a corner, hoping not only to be forgotten but maybe with enough denial eventually to be undone.
¬∑
and despite what the world sees or others opinion of what you should feel or how you should heal, the hardest battle is the one we have within ourselves. and the most difficult truth is the one we can only face alone.
¬∑
but despite the harm that was caused or the days that went dark, you did what you needed to heal. and you walked a path that only you can truly understand because all you could do was learn how to put back the pieces and soothe the most fragile parts of your soul.
¬∑
but my dear, please know this: your ability to rebuild is far greater than anyones attempt to destroy. and your truth far more powerful than anyones attempt to silence.
¬∑
so as you move forward today and as you navigate the most difficult corners of your soul, know that you are not alone. for the love, support and guidance that surrounds you can never be shacken.
¬∑
you are strong. you are whole. & you are complete. and those are the truths can never be undone. with love, sarah kreuz / @spiritual.hacks
¬∑

text:
my overwhelming thoughts from yesterday are: i believe dr. christine blasey ford. she is brave beyond measure. i am sick over what happened to her in high school, and what she has had to endure for all of her years following. now she is facing death threats during a time that she is having to relive her attack more vividly and more completely than ever before. she felt so strongly compelled to do her civic duty by telling the truth about her attacker, that she chose to make her trauma public and put herself in danger. no woman, child, or man should ever have to go through what she has gone through.

the reality is that more of us will go through what she is going through. more of us will be raped, sexually assaulted, or sexually harassed. plenty of us already have been. inevitably some of our attackers will seek positions of power, and more people will be faced with the choice that dr. ford was forced to make. that is terrifying. 
thinking about her decision i was reminded of the train dilemma. do you switch the tracks to run over one person and save the lives of five other people, or do you do nothing and allow for the 5 to be killed? i believe dr. ford was the one person on the other track and she switched the track anyways. 
thank you dr. christine blasey ford. thank you for the truth. 
#metoo #believesurvivors

text: this particular piece of seaglass is very special.  it will be used as the sunrise in a collage for an upcoming book i‚Äôm working on with one of my daughters; it will be just the beginning.  seaglass holds very profound meaning for us... for me.  i want to be seaglass.  think about it.  things, perhaps useful, functional things become damaged through abuse or misuse or are considered obsolete and they are thrown away.  they end up in a dump or on a trash barge hauled out to sea. bits of broken, shattered, ‚Äòuseless junk‚Äô are dumped and spend decades alone in the dark, cold recesses of the ocean.  there it is turned and tumbled, refined and smoothed until it is often unrecognizable.  the ocean eventually washes it to her shores, now covered in fine crystalline coatings that shimmer in the sunlight and disappear in water to reveal hidden mysteries of color and charm to all those who venture a gaze within.  its silent, extraordinary beauty defies explanation or description.  it has truly become anew, something to bring joy and delight, something held aloft to catch the glimmer of the suns rays, something strung around one‚Äôs next and held close to the heart as a cherished memento used to relive memories of summer walks on the shore.  it becomes a treasure beloved, not merely functional, if it ever once was indeed.  it simply becomes..., again.  i want to be seaglass.  #beseaglass #metoo #ibelievechristineblaseyford #ibelieveyou #ibelieveinyou

Ÿà ÿ¨Ÿàÿßÿ® ÿß€åŸÜŸá: ÿ™Ÿà ŸÇÿØÿ±ÿ™ ÿ™ÿ∫€å€åÿ± ÿ≤ŸÜÿØ⁄Ø€å‚Äåÿ™ ÿ±Ÿà ÿØÿßÿ±€å. ÿØ€å⁄ØŸá ÿØŸÜÿ®ÿßŸÑ Ÿæÿßÿ≥ÿÆ ÿ≥ÿ§ÿßŸÑÿßÿ™ÿ™ ÿ™Ÿà€å ÿß€åŸÜÿ™ÿ±ŸÜÿ™ ŸÜ⁄Øÿ±ÿØ. ÿ™Ÿà ÿ¨Ÿàÿßÿ® ÿ±Ÿà ŸÖ€å‚ÄåÿØŸàŸÜ€å. ÿ™Ÿà ÿßÿ®ÿ≤ÿßÿ±ÿ¥ ÿ±Ÿà ÿØÿßÿ±€å.

text:
my nephew, baby h, is 1 and i am overjoyed. one year ago, when he came to this world, he made my belief in miracles even stronger. ever since he was a fetus, i shared an intangible bonding with him. i‚Äôd watch him on the monitor in doctor‚Äôs clinic, moving his tiny arms and legs in his mummy‚Äôs womb and with each tiny move my heart would smile with joy. i‚Äôd hear his tiny heart beating and thank the lord that he‚Äôs growing just fine. 
when my sister got pregnant, the person (who i might‚Äôve called baby h‚Äôs father had he acted like one), left her and baby h. ever since that day, that person is nothing more than a sperm giver to me as calling him a father/husband would be akin to bringing shame to the institution of a family. 
baby h, very strongly fought all the hate in my sister‚Äôs belly. the sperm giver‚Äôs father would change my sister‚Äôs prescribed medicines with cheap low quality ones in order to save money and also because he says and i quote ‚Äúitnay paison mein tou nae biwi ajati hai‚Äù. the sperm giver‚Äôs mother would ask my sister to sit down on all fours and do chores that could risk her pregnancy and put baby h‚Äôs life at risk and i quote her words, ‚Äútum mujhe ye bacha paida kar k dekhao‚Äù. the sperm giver himself asked my sister to abort the baby several times because he only wanted my sister to serve for his sexual satisfaction without bringing any financial liability upon him.
my sister survived being pregnant in a house that would count the amount of food consumed by her. the sperm giver‚Äôs mother would count the number of left over koftay in the fridge and warn my sister not to eat a single one of it. not only that, the number of bread slices, packs of milk and even the eggs were counted in that house because they thought they were the god that provides food for my sister and the tiny life that was growing in her. little did they know..
anyway, today i just want to shout it out to the world that i‚Äôm proud of baby h for his resilience and of my sister for her insurmountable strength. i have heard her cry in pain while she delivered her baby and i have watched her eyes shine with joy with baby h‚Äôs glorious laughter and babbling.
happy b‚Äôday, baby h!
love,
aanu

text:
i hear a lot how democracy is dead, how people no longer have a voice in the political process. heck, i myself have had those thoughts in some form or another. often. the struggle is real. the overwhelming nature of it all legit. news and general attention is very often focised at the federal level, occasionally at the state. but what many individual people seem to overlook is local governments. voting numbers support this. a lot of people vote when a presidential candidate is on the ballot, but are m.i.a otherwise. midterms are important. 
local is where it starts. this is where you can make a much more tangible difference. vote at all elections (please!), but do not neglect participating at the state and especially local level. you want change? then make an effort (pssst, life is effort!) to help that change happen at the most accessible level of government: local. get in the habit of exercising your right to vote, make it a priority. participate, participate, participate. we only have ourselves to blame for the loss of democracy and "freedom."
-
"by small¬†and simple things are great things brought to pass." (regardless of one's religious or non-religious affiliation, this quote from the lds book of mormon very much applies to the power of people standing up and participating in the running of this country in our currently debacled federal system. for the people, by the people. be heard. vote.)
-

#registertovote #vote #local #standup #government #usa #riseup #democracy #metoo #whyididntreport

text:
not my usual post. but i need to say this.
as a child i was sexually abused. not once. not twice. but for weeks. i didn't tell anyone. even when the cops got involved and arrested the person i claimed i hadn't been touched. i felt gross and worthless.
now that that is out of the way i can start on my rant.
america is headed down an incredibly dangerous road for two reasons.
1. men are public enemy number 1. for every legitimate predator out there, there are 100's of men that are suffering but refuse to say anything because we don't deserve to. we don't deserve to be hurt. we don't deserve to complain. we have everything handed to us on silver platters. there is a reason men 3.5 men commit suicide to every female suicide. this is furthered by the feminist movement as of late as well.
2. we cannot, and should not take accusations as evidence. our judicial system is based on the saying "innocent until proven guilty beyond a reasonable doubt." these accusations have to power to absolutely destroy lives, and are. we should make it so these people who have been hurt can speak out. but we cannot destroy peoples lives because they have been accused.
end rant.
i'd love to hear your thoughts below üëáüëá
