text:
when i was 12-16 i was not allowed to wear crop tops or spaghetti tops- my mom would never get a reason for this ban. i believe she thought covering me would protect me from possible harassment, assault or the inevitable blame should one occur. it was easier to ‚Äòcover‚Äô me than it was to explain how society blames women for the things that happen to them. it was easier to adopt and enforce a standard of social modesty than to teach gender equality and respect in the home. it was easier to imagine one could control unwanted sexual advances on a young lady by shaming her body or enforcing coverage than addressing the complex ways society suppresses and blames women and how to empower the woman despite what she stands to endure. 
this morning i woke up to a torrent of post congressional hearing posts- of friends, unable to sleep awake and sharing their stories, the ones they kept to themselves even during #metoo and i am filled with compassion. 
i ache for all that women have suffered and continue to suffer at the hands of society, of our collegues, men, and other women. 
these stories occur to me like offerings made, burned in fires of media and discussion- so that years from now (or maybe soon?) we will look back and see what we do to women.

i ache that as americans: we treat women who come forward with their stories with incredulity and disbelief instead of understanding and belief. 
but where does the desire to priorities the story of a man over a woman come from? when do we finally believe the calls of millions of women? when do we listen to the voices that say: 
i am here
my traumas have made me strong
i know the truth of what happened and happens
i believe other women-

i believe your/our attempts to discredit women exists because you/we do not want to believe that men- who you consider to be good men- do things like this. 
i believe you/we discredit women because it is easier than answering the question of how to solve the real problem: how to de-normalize rape culture, how to de-normalize hatred of women, how to build respect and compassion. how to empower women to be themselves in a society that constantly puts them down.

and suddenly here we all a

text:
a little over a year after i was raped at 14, i was diagnosed with ibs by a colonoscopy and an endoscopy. i was in an abusive relationship. i was constantly scared and stressed out. my mental state wore my physical body down to almost nothing. i lost so much weight, over 20 pounds on my already slender frame. i couldn‚Äôt eat anything without it racing out of me minutes later, not that i ever actually had an appetite. i subsisted off of ensure packets mixed in cow‚Äôs milk for breakfast, lunch, and dinner, as per my doctor‚Äôs orders üôÑüòì somedays i just wouldn‚Äôt eat anything because the pain of ‚Äúeating‚Äù was far worse than just having nothing in me at all. it was like my digestive system just shut down from all the stress. 
i missed weeks of school, it‚Äôs still a surprise to me that i even passed 11th grade. i was feeling so awful and depleted all the time. my skin was a horrible mess, i had crazy acne breakouts and my skin turned a grayish color. when the rumors started about anorexia and bulimia, i was so mortified and devastated that i didn‚Äôt even want to be around anyone in that school at all. i thought about suicide every single day for so many months. 
my abuser was now cheating on me with multiple other girls, and when i would try to break up with him he threatened to end his life. as much as i knew i didn‚Äôt want to be with him and under his spells anymore, i knew i didn‚Äôt want him to die. 
i didn‚Äôt get any reprieve from my physical symptoms until i finally had the courage to end things with my abuser for good. back then you couldn‚Äôt just block phone numbers from your phone, so my mom called our wireless provider and had them block his number. he would call me from other people‚Äôs phones, drive by my house and make sure i could see him, and ‚Äúrun into me‚Äù at parties or events. it took such a long time to finally have zero contact with this person. 
i am so grateful to be in the healthy, supportive, loving, uplifting, safe relationship that i am currently in. i never really knew how beautiful things could be with another human until i met branden @gut.back.to.nature. i love you!!!! continued below

no is no!

text:
i could never agree with a picture anymore then this one!  i would never wish being an addict on my worst enemy. waking up to hearing people in your house that are just the shadow people in your head, not being able to sleep (sober) because you're paranoid, cutting off all your friends  not going outside of your house, completely losing yourself, not remembering the last 2 years of your life.
who chooses that? no one. 
you have to come to the terms yes i made the choice to put the drugs into my body but you made the same decision when you were young at the party when you drink the same beer as i did the differences you could stop easier than i could.
we addicts are determined an addict the day were born. 
our natural dopamine levels are lower then yours. 
there's the difference. ‚Ä¢
look at it this way you have a glass , your glass is three-quarters of the way full and when you do drugs for the first time, your glass is overfilling, my glass is 1/4 of the way full & when i do drugs i'm at your level naturally without drugs; that's what makes us so susceptible to becoming an addict more than you: which classifies it as a disease.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

text:
day 271: *sigh*

it seems i have a gift for picking up the right books at the right time....which sometimes is incredibly draining.

i only got to watch a snippet of dr. ford's testimony, none of kavanaughs, but i read many articles in trying to keep informed. but honestly, i didn't even need to do that amount of research to see how things had gone. i just needed to look at the pictures. 
the stoicism of ford vs the wrath of kavanaugh was glaringly obvious by pictures alone. a woman who was reliving a traumatic event over and over and over again kept more composure than a man who still holds every advantage. and the fact is...he probably still will get his seat. because we value men's anger over women's. 
had the reactions been reversed the light would be shined different. ford would be accused of being overly emotional, erratic, incapable of being trustworthy because she couldn't maintain composure.  but its expected of men to have outbursts, to act aggressively. it's "persuasive" (in the words of senator flake this morning). i sincerely hope that senators collins, murkowski, and manchin iii do the right thing when they are called to task and block kavanaugh's confirmation. collins and murkowski especially. they are most certainly in a shit position: traitor to their party or traitor to their own gender? that is how they will be viewed. 
also...everyone make sure to take care of yourselves. i've had to limit how much of this case i read about or listen to because i'm finding it triggering. so....take care of yourselves, know when you need to take a break, protect your mental health. 
#ibelievechristineblaseyford #believesurvivors #genderpolitics #personalispolitical #supportwomen #metoo #endsexualassault

text:
dr. ford's testimony: "i am here today not because i want to be. i am terrified. i am here because i believe it is my civic duty to tell you what happened to me while brett kavanaugh and i were in high school. the details about that night that bring me here today are ones i will never forget. they have been seared into my memory and have haunted me episodically as an adult. .............. (describing the events) i yelled, hoping someone downstairs might hear me, and tried to get away from him, but his weight was heavy. i believed he was going to rape me. i tried to yell for help. when i did, brett put his hand over my mouth to stop me from screaming. this was what terrified me the most, and has had the most lasting impact on my life. i thought that brett was accidentally going to kill me." .
.
.
.

text:
‚≠ê‚≠êmy respect for woman‚≠ê‚≠ê
.
this isn‚Äôt a political post. this is a woman post.  this is a photo for my generation.
.
the courage to share her story, to face an intimidating room full of mostly men, to have her life turned upside down in service to her truth blows me away.
.
again this is not about politics for me.  of course there is another version of the story. there always is.  his life has been shattered as well, and i have compassion for him.
.
let me be clear, this isn‚Äôt about being against men.  it‚Äôs about hearing what we have to say and having compassion for all of us.
.
but do you see how many women are once again coming out of the shadows with her own stories?  when one woman courageously shares her truth, it gives all of us hope, inspiration and freedom to share ours.
.
#whyididntreportit is real. for any of us who have been traumatized, assaulted,  molested, raped, abused... there are 100 better reasons to not report it than report it.  especially when we are young, frightened and frozen. i still have not spoken about my own abuses for fear of being shamed and it being ‚Äúmy fault‚Äù. so yeah, i get it.
.
i don‚Äôt think i would have spoken up and faced what dr. christine blasey ford faced today and in the last two weeks.  so i bow down to honor her and what she did for women today.
.
thank you, dr. ford, for showing me the way to more of my own courage. üíôüíôüíô

text:
i am over the passivity of good men.
you are part of this as much as the "bad men". you do not get to wave your hands dismissively and say that you won't get involved. you dont get to ignore this. every single woman and girl you know, that has been, is in, and will be in your life, has a metoo. every single one. all over the world, regardless of age, socioeconomic status, ethnicity. regardless of if "metoo" even exists in that community, or if they have been left out of it.
i dont want to be proud of the men i know who do their research, acknowledge their privilege, stand up for women (and i am, i am proud of them), because that shouldnt be something we need to put up on a pedestal--thats something all men need to do, without being asked. that shouldn't be something to be grateful for, like a luxury. it should be a requirement to be aware. 
do not say "not all men", because you'd be missing the point. look around you and see what happens every day, and you need to be part of this. you need to go to those rallys. you need to read those articles. you need to vote. you need to defend and believe victims and survivors. you need to listen and stop being passive. we're all over it.

#metoo #stopkavanaugh #ibelievevictimsurvivors #ibelievechristineblaseyford #sexualassault #sexualviolence #sexualharassment #sexism #privilege #notallmen #eveensler

text: we, victims of sexual assault! today is a sad day and a great step in our nation regarding sexual assault victims. as a 6yr old boy i was sexually assaulted and violated by an adult woman. i remember that it took me years to tell my parents or anyone what had happened to me. i remember that day in school when the subject came up and i went to the school guidance counselor to say ‚Äúthat happened to me‚Äù. i was afraid, scared, embarrassed and confused about why my purity, sexual boundaries, and innocence was violated and taken in just a year long period. i have battled my life with the emotional pain, poor decision making and confusion that often times accompanies these traumatic moments one can never get back. i have failed at trying to medicate, mask and make-up for a moment in my life that was not my fault. i have been in recovery for the past 7 years for sex addiction because the pain was never addressed until my life and marriage came to a screeching stop. i knew that my life had become unmanageable. i have decided to share this because this is real! this is me! this is my story and journey back from a dark place to be a light in a dark world.

text: this. i spent the first hour of my workday in search of this. in case you don‚Äôt know, this little rubber disc is a critical component to a breast pump. *why is this important? * first, it reminded me of how much harder us women have to work just to be on equal footing with our male colleagues (in position only, because #paygap). usually that means busting my ass, often working late at night after i‚Äôve put my kids to bed, delicately balancing on the line between being ‚Äútoo bitchy‚Äù and ‚Äútoo soft.‚Äù recently, that means finding 3x a day in an already over-loaded schedule to pump‚Ä¶ often i find myself shoveling down my lunch while i pump, pumping while on conference calls, pumping and eating and being on conference calls all at the same time‚Ä¶ nothing has slowed down, i just have to find a way to layer it on top; us women are always ‚Äúlayering." and i will add that i consider myself extremely fortunate that my work place is incredibly flexible and supportive of my choice to do both and do both well. but today, in order to pump, i had to huff it to two different stores to try and find what i needed (they didn‚Äôt have it) and finally had a fellow working/pumping mom (üòò @lizkmcq ) come through for me. an hour. but *also* within that hour-long pursuit around my little section of the city, i was catcalled, winked at, and aggressively stared down by many men. too many to count. this is life if you are a woman. and this. all of this. this is why we are angry. this is why we believe dr. ford. this is why we are sickened and outraged by what keeps happening in our society. this is why we‚Äôre getting louder. this is why we have to vote in november. and men? text: #metoo. what is so scary about this for me, is that i was that 15 year old girl. i was also the 15 year old girl, that didn‚Äôt come forward. what happened to me, what happened to dr. ford, shouldn‚Äôt have any less gravity because of fear and the lack of a conviction in court. what scares me the most is that as a victim, she has likely been to hell and back and back again since 1982, and the man that allegedly victimized her, may very well be awarded with a seat in the most prestigious court in our country for a lifetime. there is no possibility to prove, or not prove these claims. but dr. ford has undoubtedly come forward and offered up everything possible to prove her truth, with nothing to gain. what motivation would there have been for her to bring this up in therapy dating back to 2012? or to take a polygraph? do we want a supreme court justice, where we will likely never know with 100% certainty, if he committed such a heinous act? and even more, do we want to set a precedent in this country, where we dismiss victims, and award the accused with a lifetime commitment to protect the constitution?

text:
this morning it was comforting (and felt almost necessary) to be in the company of powerful women. .
we discussed the constant dismissal of women's opinions, expertise, and value in light of the kavanaugh hearing and the general nature of the climate in our country and workplaces right now (and always).
.
i heard from women who's parents would discourage them from pursuing post-secondary education for the fear of "intimidating" a potential husband.
.
i heard from women who, like me, reported sexual harassment in the workplace in the past and were met with dismissal and comments about being "too sensitive" and "not taking a joke."
.

text:
it takes a very particular, a very insidious kind of entitlement to convince a man that he has earned a supreme court seat. it takes a very particular, a very twisted worldview. but if there‚Äôs anything to be taken from brett kavanaugh‚Äôs testimony on thursday, it‚Äôs exactly that ‚Äî he believes he‚Äôs won this appointment fair and square.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
‚Äúi busted my butt in academics,‚Äù kavanaugh offered. ‚Äúi always tried to do the best i could. as i recall, i finished one in the class.‚Äù he did sports. he ran track. he tutored and volunteered at the soup kitchen downtown. a simple set of questions lurked beneath his aggravated outbursts: shouldn‚Äôt that all be enough? don‚Äôt i deserve this? after all, that‚Äôs what kavanaugh and his peers were taught to believe. you play by the rules. you collect the winnings you‚Äôre promised that all good, smart boys deserve.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
what kavanaugh, senator lindsey graham, senator chuck grassley, and the other male members of the judiciary committee seem to misunderstand is that for women, those rules have never applied. the notion that an average, intelligent person can sail through elite circles collecting accolades all the way to the highest court in the land ‚Äî that‚Äôs a masculine worldview.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
women don‚Äôt get to fight tooth and nail for their supreme court seats because they‚Äôre busy fighting for survival. they‚Äôre busy fighting for their dignity, for their humanity. for the right to be believed when they air their traumas, or at least not to be laughed at.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä

text:
january 2004. i was 17, on a cruise with my family in the cayman islands, belize, and cozumel. having the time of my life snorkeling with sting rays, exploring ancient ruins, and soaking up the sun on catamarans. 
the girl in this picture was so happy. she had no idea that the last night of this incredible vacation would be one of the single worst experiences of her life.

i had met some kids my age and hung out with them in the teen club a few times. one boy was really cute and asked me to take a walk. it was late, no one was around, and we were looking out at the ocean in the moonlight. he kissed me, gently. i liked it. suddenly, he pushed me against the wall on deck, and started groping me. i told him to stop, tried to fight it, but i couldn‚Äôt stop him. i saw a crew member and cried for help, but they just kept walking. i don‚Äôt know if they heard me, or just ignored my cries. what happened next is something that should never happen to anyone. when he was done, i stumbled back to my cabin and cried myself to sleep, quietly so as to not wake my cousin sleeping in the bed next to mine.

the next morning i had to meet my family to disembark. i was quiet, withdrawn, and my mom asked if i was ok. was i ok? no. i wasn‚Äôt. but i couldn‚Äôt tell her that. i couldn‚Äôt tell her that this trip, this beautiful vacation, would now be tainted by one of my worst memories. that i wasn‚Äôt the same person she had said goodnight to just a mere 12 hours before.

i didn‚Äôt tell anyone. because i was ashamed. i had gone off alone with this boy, i had let him kiss me, and i‚Äôd liked it. i felt like i had done something wrong, that maybe i led him on and deserved what i got. 
i didn‚Äôt tell anyone because i didn‚Äôt know his last name, or even where he was from. i didn‚Äôt tell anyone because i had cried for help and my one saving grace had just walked away. i didn‚Äôt think anyone would believe me. and if they did, what could we do?

i didn‚Äôt tell anyone for years. i only told my mom two years ago. but i‚Äôm telling people now. 
because that 17 year old girl is changed, but she‚Äôs not broken. #metoo #believewomen #1in6

text:
openly sharing a story is not easy. fear. shame. denial. dread. repressing the terrible. we need to recognize the immense strength on display in a world where we are quick to call women liars. dr. christine blasey ford is cloaked with courage. i trust her, i believe her, and i admire her unwavering voice. ¬∑

yesterday, during the hearing, the national sexual assault hotline spiked 147%. and yet that is not all. there are still those unable to tell their story. unable to understand. unable to speak up. i know i haven't. terrified of what people might think if they knew it happened to their friend, mother, husband, sister, daughter, wife, brother. ¬∑

it can happen to anyone. on any day. at a party or in broad daylight. by someone you just met or someone you've trusted and confided in for years. by someone you respect. by someone you will continue to hang out with or by someone you may never see again. ¬∑

stay educated. read. i cannot stress the importance of reading enough. books, the news, twitter. follow what is happening in your community. talk to those around you. grow through what the community is going through. be someone others can trust and confide in. be a good human. ¬∑ & i'd be remiss to not thank @mathiaspictures for being an unwavering pillar of support. for being my equal and someone i can openly talk to about everything and anything. who will hear all sides to a story. who will engage in an educated debate. who i both learn from and teach every single day. i love you.
¬∑
¬∑
¬∑
¬∑

text:
for generations, there has been an ongoing theme that ‚Äúboys will be boys‚Äù. its gross. not because i care about gender roles necessarily as it pertains to this topic, but because we‚Äôre actually using it as an argument to defend poor choices; choices that ruin people‚Äôs lives. ....we will teach these kids better

we will teach them to hold to the door-for everyone. 
we will teach them to listen, and also to speak up.

we will provide unconditional love and acceptance. we will demonstrate that women don‚Äôt need their protection, only their support. not because they need the support of men, but because that‚Äôs what humans do.

they need to understand ‚Äúno‚Äù and understand consent. they must honor their partners and their peers. we must define boundaries and teach them about true love, peace and understanding.

we will encourage deep breathing. we will teach them that hate and bigotry have no place in our homes.

we will teach them to take responsibility for their actions and always speak truth.

boys will be men and we need to raise them accordingly.

text:
i don‚Äôt normally like to make posts about specific political issues but the amount of division i have seen on social media from citizens of this country is astounding. as always, i like to look at the big picture. so what i will say about this brett kavanaugh fiasco is, when did we become a country that only votes for the uber privileged to have these positions? maybe these accusations were false, maybe they weren‚Äôt but ford‚Äôs accounts made me think of brock turner, the stanford u student who was tried for rape. i‚Äôm sure teens in those positions get away with things the rest of us can‚Äôt, and maybe this was the case for kavanaugh. regardless, i‚Äôm sick of these yale/harvard educated officials who were in fraternities and from families who run banks and know nothing about middle and lower class. we are continually supporting men and women who do not know how to serve this country and honestly i do not think they care to serve this country anymore. i‚Äôd also like to raise a red flag that this man was involved in the recount in florida during the bush/gore election. i think most of know how that eerily seemed similar to corruption. so all i will say is stop arguing with one another over this story, and as the people should have the power, the people need to start voting in officials who will make a difference and fight for the majority. i‚Äôm not sure anyone in all of dc represents this. stop being divided people and think about the whole ‚úåÔ∏è
.

text:
i know that i have spent the last 48 hours thinking of my own #metoo moments particularly one i have never told anyone and will probably take to my grave. 
i know many many women have experienced much worse trauma from those events than i have so to them and to the rest of us i implore you to take good care of yourself today. no you do not read every story and follow the breaking news all day long. 
meditate, take a hot bath, play soothing music, find a yoga class, be with others who lift you up and support you. go to sleep early and drink lots of water. 
i have space for two massages today and tomorrow so if you need a massage private message me. 
and yes, sexual assault is not exclusive to women and the events that are unfolding daily and particularly this week hurt / concern / effect both men and women. i in no means want to diminish that. may we all heal and move towards a world with more balanced masculine and feminine energies and less abuse of power üíú
the bandaids are all getting ripped off right now, the curtains are being drawn to expose all the shadows.
we will make it thru üôè
om shiva shakti shanti namaha

text: about a year ago, i shared one of my #metoo moments online. it involved a doctor who behaved inappropriately, something i knew was wrong at 24, but dismissed because of his prominent, respected position. after telling my story, i received countless messages from other doctors urging me to report what happened to the california medical board. so i did just that. and the process was long and intimidating, culminating in a hearing with a deputy attorney general, in which i was repeatedly asked why i'd waited so long to report the issue. i didn't have a better answer than i was scared. last month i received a letter that my case had been closed as there simply wasn‚Äôt enough evidence. it made me feel as though my voice wasn‚Äôt heard and didn‚Äôt matter. but after hearing christine blasey ford‚Äôs brave testimony yesterday, it gave me hope. we may not always get the outcome we want, but as long as we continue to stand up for ourselves and other women, it‚Äôs the first step towards instilling real change.

text_retweet:
this brilliant man. @aaronxrose 
#repost @aaronxrose with @get_repost
„Éª„Éª„Éª
let‚Äôs break this down: dehumanization is a mirrored process. the way we treat others is a direct reflection of how we see ourselves. quantum physics, all spiritual traditions, and our own gut intuition tell us this.¬†‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
eradicating sexual violence goes beyond simply training men to not assault people and creating better reporting systems (though those are important steps).¬†‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
men do not rape just because they think less of others. they rape because they think less of themselves. they hurt others because they feel incomplete, because they have been conditioned to seek security & comfort externally, rather than nurturing it within themselves.¬†‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
when i look at someone like kavanaugh, i see a man who has made, like so many other men, a deal with the devil, before he was even conscious of it: trade your eternal humanity for earthly power.‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£
‚Å£
when i witness men in my workshops become emotional and irate when asked to show up with greater care for others, i see that they are fundamentally bewildered about why or how they should be giving something to someone else that they do not have themselves: true self-respect, a full range of self expression, emotional presence and gentleness. ‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£‚Å£

text:
***trigger warning for sexual assault*** i think of the lineage of broken women allowing their sons, husbands, and the world of the masculine to do as it pleases. i think of how i was groomed and trained for victimhood by the scared, hurting, broken women in my life who wouldn't rock the boat and have accepted things as they are because there seemed to be no other way to survive. 
as i go through these albums and the pictures one by one, each of these women is receiving permission to heal. i look at their faces. i see the parts of them, toxic, fearful, willful and broken and victimized by intense patriarchal ideals. i honor the reality that this also vibrates within my dna and now i speak truth to it directly. i inject the new vibration of truth, love and sovereignty. as i heal me, i heal them. maybe now they will be able to rest and me too. 
sometimes it's difficult to determine what "kinds of abuse" get the stamp of "sexual abuse". sexuality is hardwired into everything we are, feel and do. when two heterosexual men fist fight in anger there is sexual energy in that. when an artist creates anything there is sexual energy in that. admiring a beautiful day or slinging hateful thoughts toward a person we feel has harmed us is all riding on the current of sexual energy. 
sexual energy is our life force. it is the creation of all things, not just babies. it creates the good, the bad, the beautiful and the ugly. 
when our creations go haywire it means our connection to our own sexuality has gone haywire. 
re-membering our trauma... re-membering as the opposite of dis-membering. when a person is violated (even non physically) there is an attack on their sovereignty no matter the perception of others as to how big or small, normal or abnormal the violation seems to their sensibility. 
violations occur all of the time. it is not until we look at them that they begin to heal. we need to recognize them as violations and name them as what they are. we can no longer let a frightened culture hellbent on a "power over" structure do the naming on our behalf. ***continued in comments***
name: Mary Renee Nicosia

text:
would you believe if it was me who had come forward? me who spoke up? me who just wanted truths exposed? me who didn‚Äôt want to relive this, but felt it was my civic duty to do so? me who swore with 100% certainty. or would i still be questioned, degraded, and threatened?
|
so what if it was your sister, girlfriend, wife or friend...would it make a difference? would you then understand? would you then believe? believing gives hope, and supporting is powerful. the reactions you have will bring consequences, whether those are positive or negative is your decision.

in the meanwhile, i wish healing to those affected by the resurgence of memories brought about by this testimony by dr ford

text:
i am the oldest child of four girls. -
i have two daughters. -
i remember the first time this statement was made to me, in elementary school. 
my friend, a boy, starting kicking and hitting me on the bus.
-
 this was the excuse of his parents. ‚Äúoh its just because he likes you ashley. boys will be boys!‚Äù -
in middle school, i was told this again, after being bullied by a boy on my bus for being so tall. ... this was the excuse of his parents. ‚Äúoh he just likes you and is insecure because you‚Äôre taller than him right now! boys will be boys!‚Äù -
this statement has been told to me more times then i‚Äôd like to admit. 
growing up thinking that boys are mean to us simply because they are boys and we are girls and that they do it because they like us - is a mentality that we, as a generation, must end. -
because the damage does not stop when the we stop taking the bus. 
the damage doesn‚Äôt leave us after grade school. 
this mentality tells boys their actions are justified. 
and just as they get taller and older, the damages get deeper and more complicated. -
in fact, it gets much much worse. 
from physical, to verbal, to emotional tolls ... the damage. gets. worse. -
boys will be boys. 
girls will be girls. 
and people should treat one another like human fucking beings with nothing but love & compassion, regardless of what they look like or what their dna says.

text: scrolling through my photos just now looking for something else and i found this. a¬† photo i took after i left the court room where my sexual assault case was finally heard in downtown raleigh last year. my therapist wanted visual proof that i'd made it out alive. and i had. it wasn't a good photo; i hadn't slept for weeks leading up to trial but i knew she'd call me if i didn't send her something... listening to dr. ford's testimony yesterday brought back a wave of emotion; panic...pain... and awe in her strength. i had an entire year to prepare for my trial and to face the man who sexually assaulted me, dr. ford had just a few days. i got sick just thinking about reading my statement in a small court room in raleigh... dr. ford had to do it in front of the entire nation. dr. ford is the honorable one. dr. ford should be serving on the highest court in our country. she is a hero. i know she has made our country stronger. i hope dr. ford wakes up today knowing that she has changed the the trajectory of the way that our country deals with sexual assault. and most importantly, that she made it out alive. #ibelievechristineblaseyford #metoo #hero #honorable

text:
-gallup pride 2018-
queer feminist symposium starts at 10am 
emceed by lady shug 
10am-
free symposium

with this symposium we hope to spark critical dialogue and public education about a broad range of approaches to queer and feminist politics, identities, issues, and lived experiences. our presenters will openly discuss topics and experiences that challenge us to think and act differently about gender and sexuality.

many of our womxn and lgbtq2 relatives are murdered and missing in bordertowns like gallup because of violent heteropatriarchy. cis-women of color and trans-women face the majority of this violence. this symposium is aimed at helping everyone find language and courage to stop this violence.

the program features a special talk by one of the original indigenous feminists, dr. jennifer nez denetdale, who will explore how din√© (navajo) traditionalists have responded to expressions of gender diversity. other roundtables and workshops will include: the first-ever public discussion about pueblo feminism; how to have body-positive and sex-postive sex; liberation for our transgender relatives;
decolonization and queer kinship;
ending rape and human trafficking in bordertowns;
challenging cis-hetero privilege in indigenous environmental justice activism.

#decolonizegender #decolonizesexuality #queerk√©nship #indigenousfeminism #beautifullydefiant #galluppride2018 #pride #queer #feminist #metoo #timesup #allmyheroesarequeens

text:
in solidarity with so many women in #whyididntreport 
i was 15, drunk & the guy was the 20yr old manager at my job & a ‚Äúfriend‚Äù. i was asleep, i woke up to him on top of me with my clothes off. i didn‚Äôt even tell my parents or friends bc i just figured it was my fault. and let‚Äôs be honest, everyone would have agreed that it was my fault. my fault for being there, my fault for drinking, my fault for falling asleep where i did. no one would have called it sexual assault. there was zero conversation about consent & i would have been completely slut shammed & we shared so many friends at the time & he had a girlfriend. it seemed like the best thing to do, the only thing to do, was to just pretend it didn‚Äôt happen. just shove it way way down. 
i don‚Äôt really think about him, but today i wonder if he has children. does he have a daughter? 
i share my story for all those who can‚Äôt share theirs. 
in my line of work..... these kinds of stories are shared every day. it‚Äôs my job to create a safe place to share & unravel these experiences from our bodies, by holding space, bodywork & herbal healing, & just listening. unfortunately... this stuff is waaaaaaay to common. .
#rapeculture #timesup #wewearblack #enoughisenough #believesurvivors #ibelieveher #sexualassault #metoo

text:
on wednesday night, in a very safe neighborhood, i was asked if i wanted someone to go with me to walk the two blocks to my car. because #sexualassault is all too common. 
1 in 5 women are victims of sexual assault every year in the us.
every 98 seconds, someone is sexually assaulted in the us, and 9 out of 10 victims are women.
stop. believing. socialized. patriarchy.

i will teach my son to defend those with no voice. 
i will teach my son to be an ally.

text_retweet:
today i read this feeling a little lighter. i shared one of my many assault survival stories with my husband last night. he held the space, he did not make me feel stigmatized or judged, and he helped me come to terms with a lot of the hard realities of what i lived through and what brought me to that point, and to this space now where i can feel that and not crumple under the weight of it but come out from under that pain and shame feeling stronger and more connected - not less. he believed me. he made me feel safe. he is a shining star of what it means to be fully whole and fully hold the space for another and himself. he was honest with me but also himself about how he felt hearing about what happened to me. he held me, he let me cry. he wiped the tears and knew, he understood.
.
after watching dr. ford‚Äôs testimony after the fact and hearing about the several other women with evidence against mr. kavanaugh, i pray the world hears and sees what is happening. we are waking up from the mass hypnosis that we don‚Äôt matter. we are waking up. let‚Äôs continue to catch and hold each other as we unfold and become who we truly are.
.

text:
a friend asked how i was feeling in the wake of dr. ford‚Äôs testimony.  i said:

i waited to watch the news until midnight because i needed to focus yesterday without feeling the edges of terror.  honestly, all i felt was empathy and familiarity.  very sad and hated the backlash because that‚Äôs what keeps women silent, but i‚Äôm glad she had the courage to speak.  i think she felt like should couldn‚Äôt not. 
i can‚Äôt feel guilt for not going to the police at 21 and stopping those men from doing it again and again armed with plenty of money and lots of rohypnol because i felt like it was my fault and no one would believe it was non consensual.  even though a drug test and a rape kit would have evidenced otherwise.  sigh.  i just wanted to go home and scrub my body inside and out like ethan hawk in gattaca. literally my skin was red for days from scrubbing. 
i probably shouldn‚Äôt have watched dr ford‚Äôs sworn statement in full at midnight alone. i recognize that, but i needed to hear her yesterday while all this was going on but at a time when it wouldn‚Äôt overtake me. 
i didn‚Äôt have night terrors as a result.  i have day time terror that even with the fbi polygraph indication that her statements were true, and her reputation and expertise, she‚Äôs still treated like a dumb kid who brought it on herself by being at a party with drinking where boys will be boys.  dr. ford thank you so much for having the courage to do what i could not.

text: work was great. life is a lil complicated tho. a meditation in three parts - a) michelle goldberg nyt 9/27/18 - a beautiful & devastating closing statement to her op-ed. my rage is not measured in black words on a white screen - it is a 10-story chemical fire, a sonic boom, a cat 5 hurricane, and a monster born of a lifetime‚Äôs fury & proof. it was never about snowflakes or winter. this is about a seismic, catastrophic event. b) kali mala beads - so many times, they help to stop & refocus & channel the volcanic lava of energy & anger into something useful - maybe the highest & best use of that deadly flow of lava & fire is to destroy. to tear this godforsaken empire down, so we can build one that values every human. over & over until the end of time. me & my women, the sisterhood of survivors, we‚Äôll be just fine. we will march, scream & dance to the tune of destruction. we ignite & crumble to dust & are phoenixes reborn from the flames. let‚Äôs torch it & demand excellence. the dream is worth it. c) so much love & fluff in 15-pound dog, lucia is the balm for a batteredsoul. super good @ snuggles, v talented at cleaning away tears, and down right stellar at playing with squeaker toys. open to meeting new friends & loving up on them esp if is a hard day. thank you to all the lovely people living up to their best ‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è‚ô•Ô∏è #whatdidwedotodeservedogs #believewomen #survivorsrage #finalwavefeminism #getonboardorgetoutoftheway #burnitdown #midterms2018 #gooddog #listentoblackwomen #metoo #lgbtqiarightsforever #demandbetterfromyourpoliticians #demandbetterfromyourfriends #makeitsafeforwomen #bringyourdancingboots #meetmeattheendoftheworld #crushthepatriarchy ‚úäüèª‚úäüèº‚úäüèΩ‚úäüèæ‚úäüèøüíã

text:
if you're questioning whether or not that thing that happened to you was assault, you're not alone. this happened last year with #metoo and it's happening again now. as more women find the strength to stand up and share the story of the violence perpetrated against their bodies, more of us are seeing our stories in theirs.

this period of reckoning can be confusing. it was for me.

for 12+ years, i talked myself out of it. i was ashamed that it happened, embarrassed that it happened to me, and all i wanted after it happened was to escape. i didn't call the police. i didn't go to the hospital. i didn't tell anyone until i told my husband last year.

i told myself that because i didn't fight back, i must have wanted it. i didn't fight back because i didn't know how. i had to choose: if i fight back, he might kill me. if i pretend to be sleeping, i might survive. i pretended to sleep.

i told myself that maybe my no wasn't firm enough the night before. or maybe consent (or the lack thereof) is an agreement that must be renewed at midnight. maybe i just didn't say no loud enough or firm enough or in the right way. 
if you are a survivor and you are feeling all the feelings this week, give this a listen when you want to feel a little less alone.

in this episode i talk about how the trail helped me connect the dots around how surviving a sexual assault 12 years ago affected my life.

text_retweet:
a popular fb friend reposted this and i made the heart. .
.
.

mindfulness practice these days is raising my empathy meter. although contributing to its decrease came from statements like, ‚Äúwow, look at there. you‚Äôre 3rd great grandmother‚Äôs obituary says she was a good slave and house woman after emancipation. it notes the plantation which is now a bed and breakfast. just think, you can save up and spend the night where you‚Äôre ancestors lived @wiltonhousevirginia ‚Äú, said the volunteer @familysearch genealogist. now...
.
.
i‚Äôm usually blankly dismissive to ignorance. that statement had me screaming at the top of my lungs inside of my head. i was at the @usnatarchives , library voice only. thinking, what the hell makes you think i want to sleep where my ancestors were enslaved. .
.
.
that was almost 5 years ago. the next day, i went to @westmorelandcountymuseum to visit montross westmoreland county. darlene was very helpful. i found out the house noted atwilton was not a typo and there was a plantation there by that name. 
hold on... i need to blog this. .
.
.

all to say, just last week i called the @wiltonhousevirginia and @wiltonhousemuseum to inquire about the family history of the estates and crossed them off my list. .
.
.

what took me so long? i was so busy fighting that statement, i didn‚Äôt have the clarity  of mind to make two 2 minute calls. .
.
.

text: this week is triggering af. i've never been forced to share my story and i cannot imagine the turmoil that it would cause me to do so. the idea that anyone who has lived through sexual assault or coercion has to stand and defend themselves, defend one of the most complex and painful experiences of their life to the entire nation makes my chest so heavy. i just want to hibernate from all media for a week. if you're feeling hurt by this whole thing on a personal level, i see you, i feel you - we're going to get through this shit time together üíï #metoo

text:
hi i‚Äôm kendall. i live in northern michigan and create these little squares while working for myself and creating weddings for a living.
.
.
.
in 2015 i filed a lawsuit against the department of the interior while working for the national park service - actually after i was let go from the national park service - after reporting the sexual harassment i was experiencing from my supervisor.
.
.
.
it was long. it was arduous. it was traumatizing over and over again. it resulted in further harassment from the eeo officer that was assigned to my case. it involved all of the usual questions, if you‚Äôre unfamiliar with the usual questions, i‚Äôll share them with you:
.
what did he do? (please describe in detail so we can determine if it was actually bad)
.
did you ask him to stop? (why not?)
.
were you being too friendly or forward? (you seem friendly and forward)
.
why didn‚Äôt you say something sooner? (if it was so bad, why did it go on for three months?)
.
he‚Äôs never treated me different, why would he behave this way to you? (there must be something wrong with you)
.
what do you want us to do? (our sexual harassment policy actually stops here)
.
you chose to quit, didn‚Äôt you? (you could have stayed and worked this out, but you‚Äôre a quitter)
.
.
.
i eventually ran out of energy. i ran out of resources. after 6 months i was so tired of being isolated. it has a way of doing that. so i accepted a bribe, aka a settlement at the american taxpayer‚Äôs expense in my requested amount of the income i had lost, nothing more than workwoman‚Äôs comp for the inconvenience of having a female body, and we moved back to michigan.
.
.
.
i found a new job with nps and started over briefly. i‚Äôm really good at starting over. it turns out i‚Äôm excellent at representing myself. being a good writer helped, a privilege i exhausted in the process. my account, like so many others will never show up in the public record, only mine. knowing it would dissolve with my fight, i knew i had to write it for me too.
.
.
.
thank you, to every silence breaker for introducing your story so that we are a little less alone when the world asks of us ‚Äútell me about yourself".

the truth about kavanaugh we will never know and this is not a post about siding with one or the other. people want to judge blasey for not coming out sooner if it was true. instead of posing the question of why did she not come out sooner? here‚Äôs a few reasons i‚Äôm sure crossed her mind... 1. who would believe me?

3. what will people think of me? 
4. maybe i caused this? 
5. what would it change? 
6. will people look at me as damaged? 
we have to change our society‚Äôs way of thinking. like today! 
we need to make it a safe place to come forward and let the victim choose how to proceed. 
the victim should be taught to feel empowered for having the strength to come out! 
we should speak positivity and love back into there broken soul. 
expressing the choice was not there‚Äôs it was taken and that they did nothing to deserve it. let it change the future for victims. 
freeing their voices to speak the forbidden truth.

we must change the world for the futures of all man kind! i stand by all of you who are out there! keep on fighting the good fight! you are beacons of bravery!

text:
signs of fall are filling me with feelings of dread. as someone who loves change and beautiful colors this has been baffling to me. i think it stems from a fear of letting go. i love heat. will i  still be here when it gets really cold? will i have to deal with snow? what am i even doing here? 
but yet i know that when it is cold, i love that too. i'm enjoying this chilly day. i'm enjoying unique chilly day cloud formations. the waning moon behind some chilly clouds. when it gets really cold, i'll love that too, if i'm still here.

i wish i could communicate to people who are accustomed to having privilege that they will get used to losing it.  white men will get used to being held accountable for their actions. i know it's scary. but it's not bad. they will get used to seeing everyone, including the trees and clouds, as their equals. it will be ok.  chilly weather and falling leaves will also be ok.

text:
üî•holding space üî•
we are collectively experiencing the aries full moon (warrior) conjunct chiron (wounded healer, trauma) in libra season justice, venus (the feminine) in scorpio (pulling up dead bodies). this morning i woke up heavy. so heavy. mad. sad. scared. fearless. i feel the weight of your shame. 
woman take back your power
i got my kids ready for school and have so much shit to do today, but i can‚Äôt stop crying, dancing, burning shit, writing down words, channeling experiences and burning that shit in the fire.. to the point i can‚Äôt sit down. i‚Äôve run, i‚Äôve done push ups, i lifted weights feeling the need to physically send strength to every woman who has been cast off or told it‚Äôs their fault, they shouldn‚Äôt dress that way, eve shouldn‚Äôt  have given adam the apple, all the grief, all the shame, all the scapegoating all that bullshit... i feel the collective weight of our grandmothers as i pace my living room hands at our back pushing the balance of justice forth. 
the reckoning is here‚Ä¶ she is here the great maiden mother crone is here. üî•
today i am going to the woods to pick up sticks for every person i feel pulling through and tonight will do a burning ceremony. i will dance. i will call out for your pain and trauma. i will use the healing taurus moon energy to collectively burn the pain, fear, shame for women. in solidarity. it won‚Äôt burn away the trauma or our stories- it will make space for the courage to step forth bravely.
if you have a word, experience, anything you feel led to share you can post below if you want to pm me, do so. if you want to send the energy my way, that works too. 
i see you. i hear you. your story matters. you matter. #ibelieveyou #icare #metoo #forourgrandmothers #healing #aries #taurusmoonmystic #metoomovement #forthewomen #risesisterrise #divinefeminine #transformation #womenwhorunwiththewolves #wild #firemedicine

text:
hi, this is hannah starkey posting on #tpgallery ‚Äì day 2
the woman‚Äôs march on 21st january 2017 was a revolution long overdue, and i felt that it was going to be driven as much by the visual as by words. the collision of image and text in a photograph is a very powerful force for a photographer to work with. the sheer number of beautifully designed, imaginative and smart signs that day was a testament to how deeply the creators had thought about what they were doing. the power of these signs in an image driven society is immediate and direct. they were made to be photographed and then beamed around the world to speak for us all. 
#myclothesarenotmyconsent #metoo #nationalgallery #womensmarch #hannahstarkey

text:
#metoo

in light of ford/kavanaugh, i feel compelled to share my experience of sexual assault:
.
3.5 years ago, i was raped. it took me over 8 months to even be able to remember the incident, to even feel like i could use the word. i never reported him. .
i‚Äôd been out in nyc for the evening, at a few bars in my neighborhood. i met a guy, and we spent the next 3 hours talking, getting to know each other, and having a lot of fun. i was very attracted to him. so when he invited me back to his apartment, i consented. .
once he closed the door to his bedroom, the energy changed. something felt off. i suddenly felt scared. i tried to communicate- saying ‚Äúsomething doesn‚Äôt feel right‚Äù, ‚Äúhold on‚Äù, ‚Äúi don‚Äôt feel good about this‚Äù and ‚Äústop‚Äù, but he proceeded to take off his clothes and mine and then have his way. .
i remember being terrified, in massive amounts of pain, and trying desperately not to cry out, scream, sob, or let any emotion escape. too terrified to scream or fight back, i waited for it to be over in my emotional paralysis. i was so bewildered by the fact that my earlier protests seemed to be meaningless that i walked away from this thinking it was normal. after all, it was my fault right? i had agreed to go home with a stranger.
.
it took me over 8 months to realize that none of this was my fault. i had clearly verbalized that i was uncomfortable, that i had said stop three times. but when your words fall on deaf ears, when your voice is completely ignored it‚Äôs like being told you don‚Äôt exist. that you don‚Äôt matter. .
why did i not report him? because i was afraid. i was afraid that it would shock him, that he would hate me, blame me, make me feel even more shame than i already felt. and quite frankly i couldn‚Äôt handle even more shame. .
i am so grateful to dr. ford for her bravery. to stand in her truth in the midst of a painful interrogation which is another form of the same assault she and all those of #metoo have endured. .
this is a vital moment for us all. for those who have been victims of this pervasive underbelly of our society. i hope it opens all of us to be more vocal in our truth, and be more present in listening to each other.

text:
it's a new day. remember who you are. remember you are not defined by your mistakes, nor are you defined by the crimes committed against you.
.
yesterday on my blog, tamaracanup.com, i opened up about my sexual assault. the whole truth. in the 13 years since i was assaulted, it was the first time i said it all. all of it. it was the first time even my partner knew certain things. but, it was time. in the wake of what's happening in this country, i finally felt strong enough to just let it all out.
.
and doing so reminded me that this experience i had when i was 19 years old does not define me. it was a chapter. it was a painful chapter, but just a chapter nevertheless and i am so much more than just one chapter in my life that has finally ended.
.
i'm writing one helluva chapter right now actually. a chapter where i love myself and my body more than i ever have. a chapter where i'm working with amazing brands and getting paid for my freelance work. a chapter where my marriage is stronger than ever and my kiddo is thriving as well. this is by far one of the best chapters i've ever written. and my story is just getting started.
.
your story is still being written. if you're a survivor of sexual assault like me, i want you to remember that. we write our own stories. and we will rise again and shine and write one helluva story.
.
.

name: Tamara Moon-Graves
tweet_full:
it is a new day. remember who you are. remember you are not defined by your mistakes, nor are you defined by the crimes committed against you.
.
yesterday on my blog, tamaracanup.com, i opened up about my sexual assault. the whole truth. in the 13 years since i was assaulted, it was the first time i said it all. all of it. it was the first time even my partner knew certain things. but, it was time. in the wake of what's happening in this country, i finally felt strong enough to just let it all out.
.
and doing so reminded me that this experience i had when i was 19 years old does not define me. it was a chapter. it was a painful chapter, but just a chapter nevertheless and i am so much more than just one chapter in my life that has finally ended.
.
i am writing one helluva chapter right now actually. a chapter where i love myself and my body more than i ever have. a chapter where i am working with amazing brands and getting paid for my freelance work. a chapter where my marriage is stronger than ever and my kiddo is thriving as well. this is by far one of the best chapters i have ever written. and my story is just getting started.
.
your story is still being written. if you are a survivor of sexual assault like me, i want you to remember that. we write our own stories. and we will rise again and shine and write one helluva story.
.
.
.
.

text:
i made this #quotestagram last week and was going to use it to post about self-care and creativity. but i have something bigger to talk about today.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
this is not a shiny instagram moment; the last couple of days have been really hard. no matter your politics, listening to dr. christine ford re-live her trauma yesterday was excruciating. after hearing her testify with grace and patience, i find it hard to believe that anyone doubts her experience. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
not gonna lie, every time this topic gets brought up in the media and in the general public, i get preemptively tired. i know all the conversations i'm going to have about the injustices that women deal with daily. i know about the inevitable mansplaining i will face from those who are "just playing devil's advocate". i know the need to do something, and the hours of impassioned postcard writing, and impending calls to reps. i know my own trauma, and the traumas of countless others- women and men- are going to get dug up and re-lived in all of our imaginations as we listen to the brave ones share their stories. it's not just tiring...it's exhausting.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it is so tempting when you are that depleted to just give in to the anger and quit. to feel like those postcards, calls, and attempts at open dialog with those who disagree with you continue to fall on chronically deaf ears.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
but the truth is: things are changing. we have a long way to go, but the cracks in the veneer of the patriarchy are growing wider every day.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
so scream, cry, write those postcards, make those calls, raise your voice in the chorus that demands a change in the way we deal with assault and shaming. and when your voice gets tired, rest. the rest of us will chime in and hold your place until you're ready to jump back in the fight. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
rest. but please, never, ever quit.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
if you're a survivor & need to talk, you can call 800-656-hope to reach a national, confidential helpline 24/7. there is also an online hotline here -> https://hotline.rainn.org/online/

text: i could have been dr. christine blasey ford. this is me at a new years eve party years ago. i was drinking, i got drunk. i met a guy there. we talked, we flirted, we started making out. before i knew it, we were upstairs, away from the party and he was on top of me. we were both drunk. he wanted to have sex, i didn't. when he tried to undo my pants, i said no. i said i wasn't comfortable, we just met. i was afraid someone might walk in, i knew i was drunk and didn't think it was good idea. he paused, got off me, adjusted himself, gave me a hand up, and we went back down stairs. i tell this story bc too many of my friends have been sharing their why i didn't report stories, and too many of them start just like mine with a very different out come. i tell this story because i'm so sick of hearing that because a man is drinking it's excusable, but when a woman is drinking she's irresponsible. the guy i mentioned was dtf, he wanted to have sex, he could have over powered me, he didn't. do not believe the lie that men can't stop themselves, do not believe the lie that because you were drinking, you had it coming. you have every right to say no, to say stop, at any time. we need to have a higher standard for our guys. what happened to me should be the rule, not the exception.  to all the survivors, thank you for sharing your story, thank you for being brave, and i'm so sorry you are all having to relive your trauma right now. i love you and i believe you ‚ù§. #notkavanaugh #ibelievechrisitneblaseyford #metoo #whyididntreport #believesurvivors #iloveyou

text:
there is a world of silent shame. where we are told from birth how we must be extra careful of ourselves and to always be aware of the public eye. that predators lurk around every corner. we will be put down, made lesser than, taken advantage of and it is somehow our fault. the responsibility has always been one sided. why is that?

they weren‚Äôt wrong. i have felt that judgement my whole life. this is the battle we must all face. silence will help no one. for those who choose to pass judgement on the women who‚Äôve been shamed into silence, there is a special place in hell for you. i‚Äôve had enough. it‚Äôs taken years for me to recognize it is absolutely in my right to express myself and hold myself (and those around me) accountable. it is frightening to take on battles which i‚Äôve been conditioned to ignore. 
before my aug court case i was a wreck. not because i had any doubts over the course of my actions, but for fear of the potential repercussions. somewhere in court filings is a recording of me responding to a judge when asked if i had told my aggressor more than once to stop. i countered with, ‚Äúdoes it take more than once?‚Äù once should be enough. ‚Äúno‚Äù is universal. the court process took less than a month to complete. as validating as it is to have won my restraining order battle which guarantees me legal safety, i would like to add it took me 5months to finally come forward and take action. it probably would‚Äôve taken longer or perhaps never happened under different political circumstance. this is just one story. to all the women who‚Äôve been fighting in silence, know we are listening.  to my support group, i thank you for holding my hand, your guiding wisdom, letting my cry into your chest, distracting me as i had to regroup multiple times just while driving the 30min to the courthouse. our time to stand and fight is now.
photo credit @mbmoore  #empoweringwomen #fightback #speakyourtruth #metoo #timesup #rapeculture #justice #impact #breakingthesilence #thisneedstostop #findyourvoice #youarenotalone #believeher

text: i understand that false accusation is a major problem, and i am not necessarily defending any one person. however, unless if you were there, you do not know if the assault occurred or not. just because a woman comes out years later about an assault or there is no physical evidence does not mean that it didn‚Äôt happen. i was sexually assaulted, many times, over the course of several years. i never had any physical evidence. however, i felt dirty- like i could never be clean again. i damaged my body because i thought  i deserved it, and that the whole thing was my fault. i slept in the same room as my mother for years because that was the only way i felt safe. i refused to talk to strangers and had anxiety attacks over doing so because i was afraid that it would happen again. i would eat until i was sick or eat only a cup of yogurt in a day because at least i had control of my diet, because i had no control over what happened to my own body. so why did i suffer and wait four years? because i didn‚Äôt think it was sexual assault, and i thought no one would have believed me. and had it not been noticed, it would probably still be a secret. so please, just stop talking and making posts about it. because many of you have no idea. #metoo

text:
let me tell you a story. it requires a little context so i‚Äôll sum it up as briefly as i can.
when i was 6 years old, an adult male family member put his hands underneath my clothes for the first time. he told me it was to check to see if i was growing properly. i believed him. 
when i was 10 years old, i learned about sexual abuse sitting at my desk in fourth grade. i made the connection in my brain but kept quiet.
when i was 12 years old i told my family.
when i was 12 years old, my grandmother called me a liar. my grandfather told me to clean up the mess i had made. 
i was 12 years old and my grandmother said to me ‚Äúgod knows what really happened. and when we go to trial, god‚Äôs truth will be made known‚Äù.
when i was 15 years old i testified in massachusetts. i was told that i couldn‚Äôt talk about anything that happened out of state, and so much had happened in rhode island. i was taken off the stand twice because i was shaking so hard i could not speak. during recess, my aunt and grandmother walked briskly by me and refused to acknowledge my presence. 
two days later, the jury deemed my uncle not guilty. he walked out of that court with a cleared name, into the arms of the rest of my family. i walked out with the brand of a liar and into the arms of guilt and shame. it took me a long time to realize the shame was not mine to carry. my abuser played a sweet magic trick and somehow switched places with me- getting all the love and support a wounded child needed so desperately, while leaving me to clean up the mess. i spent a long time stomping around making shit messier. i spent a long time being angry and incensed that i meant so very little to what at the time felt like so many people.
if it were up to me at the time, i wouldn‚Äôt have testified. i might not have even told anyone had i not been ‚Äúouted‚Äù by a friend who loved me and wanted me safe. and i didn‚Äôt even know people didn‚Äôt support victims of sexual assault/ sexual abuse. i didn‚Äôt even know that. i remember hearing my grandmothers words about god‚Äôs truth being made known and thinking ‚Äúwell, gee, at least that will happen‚Äù. and then it didn‚Äôt. and i felt like god didn‚Äôt love me either.
.
(continued...)

text: it didn‚Äôt have to go down like this. he could have responded in a way that acknowledged her pain, took ownership over the person he was at 17 and still become a judge. he‚Äôs had a good record, he‚Äôs worked very hard but he did do the things she said. there‚Äôs not a shred of confusion on that. and he could have just been honest and kind. i have heard a lot of men say they‚Äôre confused about what women want. they don‚Äôt even know how to ‚Äúdate women now‚Äù in the era of #metoo. that men are somehow the victims of some feminist plot to change all the rules. it‚Äôs pretty simple. going forward do the right thing. treat women like humans. don‚Äôt force your desires on someone else. communicate. be able to hear no without throwing a fit.  and if you have times in your past when you have failed to behave correctly‚Äîapologize fully and provide an opportunity for restitution. you can‚Äôt change the past but you can change everything for a person in a moment by believing them. this would be a very different day if judge kavanaugh had 1. listened to dr blasey ford 2. acknowledged her pain and believed her and 3. said he was sorry even if he doesn‚Äôt remember.  that is what we are asking for guys. to the brett kavanaughs, david menerts and justin gunn‚Äôs of this world. do better.

text:
when i was a little kid, a boy i knew showed me his penis and made me touch it and kiss it. i didn't know it was wrong until later. 
when i was 15 i got really really drunk and a guy put his hand down my pants and groped me. i never said anything, because it was probably my fault for getting drunk around a boy and i didn't want to tell my parents i got drunk.
countless times during my teens guys would grope me, catcall, kiss me without my consent. but i'm sure it was because the way i dressed, so it wasn't their fault, right?
when i was 16,the assistant manager, my boss's brother in law, would say dirty things to me over the headset, like telling me to bend over a little more to see my boobs and tell me the things he wanted to do to me. i liked his sister in law, my boss, and i liked his wife, and i'm sure somehow it was my fault because my boobs were big and you could always see my cleavage, and i didn't want to lose my job.
when i was 18, i was at a party with some friends and kind of flirted with a guy, so my "friend" shoved me into a room with him and blocked the door. the guy started kissing me and held me down on the bed until i freaked out, jumped up, beat on the door, and took off. i was drinking around a boy and flirted with him, though, so i guess that was my fault.
i've never admitted to any of these things before out loud, because i lways felt ashamed and that somehow i am the one to blame. who would believe me anyways? i was asking for it. i have no proof. i would be ruining a man's life. i would lose friends. it wasn't their fault, because guys will be guys. it was just "fun & games".
fuck you #lindsaygraham for shaming a victim!
